T* (                "scene": "moon",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Borrowed Light",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "The Moon shines bright enough to read by -- yet it makes no light of its own. So where does ) Tj
T* (moonlight really come from?") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "For thousands of years, people told stories about the glowing Moon. Sailors steered ships ) Tj
T* (by it. Farmers harvested under it. You have probably seen it shine through your window.\\n\\nBut here's the mystery: the ) Tj
T* (Moon is just a giant ball of **rock and dust**. Rocks don't glow. Pick one up tonight -- does it shine? No. So why does ) Tj
T* (that rock in the sky blaze silver-bright?\\n\\nThe answer teaches us something powerful: some things in the sky **make** ) Tj
T* (light, and other things only **bounce** it. Telling those apart is one of an astronomer's most important skills.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "There are two kinds of bright things:\\n\\n1. **Light makers**, like the Sun, fires, and ) Tj
T* (lamps. They create their own light.\\n2. **Light bouncers**, like mirrors, the white pages of a book, and... the Moon. ) Tj
T* (They only reflect light that hits them.\\n\\n**The Moon is a light bouncer.** Moonlight is really **sunlight** that ) Tj
T* (traveled to the Moon, bounced off its dusty gray surface, and then traveled on to your eyes. Every moonbeam is ) Tj
T* (secondhand sunshine.\\n\\nYou can prove the idea with a flashlight and a gray ball in a dark room. The ball is invisible ) Tj
T* (in the dark -- until your flashlight hits it. Then it 'glows.' Turn the flashlight off and the glow is gone instantly. ) Tj
T* (The Moon works exactly the same way, with the Sun as the flashlight.\\n\\nHere's something surprising: the Moon is ) Tj
T* (actually a **bad** mirror. Its dusty surface is dark gray, like an old road. It bounces back only a little of the ) Tj
T* (sunlight that hits it. So why does it look dazzling? Two reasons:\\n\\n- The Sun is **incredibly** bright, so even a small) Tj
T* ( bounce is a lot of light.\\n- We usually see the Moon against the **black night sky**, where even a little light looks ) Tj
T* (brilliant -- the way one candle looks bright in a dark room but invisible at noon.\\n\\nThat also solves another puzzle: ) Tj
T* (you can sometimes see the **Moon in the daytime**! It's up there bouncing sunlight just the same, but against a bright ) Tj
ET
endstream
