(The Moon **travels around Earth** about once a month.\\n\\nNow put it together. As the Moon circles us, we see its sunlit ) Tj
T* (half **from different angles**. Sometimes the bright half faces us straight on. Sometimes it faces away. Usually we see ) Tj
T* (part bright and part dark.\\n\\n**The phases, in order:**\\n\\n- **New Moon** -- the Moon sits between Earth and the Sun. ) Tj
T* (Its lit side faces *away* from us, so we see almost nothing. The Moon seems to vanish.\\n- **Waxing Crescent** -- a thin ) Tj
T* (sliver of the lit side peeks at us. *Waxing* means **growing**.\\n- **First Quarter** -- we see half of the lit side: a ) Tj
T* (bright half circle. \(It's called a quarter because the Moon is one quarter of the way around its trip.\)\\n- **Waxing ) Tj
T* (Gibbous** -- more than half bright, still growing. *Gibbous* means bulging.\\n- **Full Moon** -- Earth is between the Sun) Tj
T* ( and Moon, and the entire sunlit face beams at us. The whole disc glows.\\n- **Waning Gibbous** -- now shrinking. ) Tj
T* (*Waning* means **shrinking**.\\n- **Last Quarter** -- half lit again, the *other* half this time.\\n- **Waning Crescent** ) Tj
T* (-- a final thin sliver... and then New Moon again.\\n\\nThe full cycle takes about **29.5 days** -- roughly a ) Tj
T* (month.\\n\\nThe most important thing to remember: **the Moon itself never changes shape.** It is always a complete ball, ) Tj
T* (always half lit by the Sun. The only thing that changes is **how much of that lit half we can see from Earth**. The ) Tj
T* (phases are a matter of *viewpoint*, not of the Moon growing and shrinking.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
