(              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "When the Apollo astronauts stepped onto the Moon, they entered a world running on ) Tj
T* (completely different rules. The sky above them was **black at noon**. The silence was total -- clap your hands and you'd) Tj
T* ( hear nothing. Their boot prints pressed into dust that hadn't moved in a billion years.\\n\\nNASA is planning to send ) Tj
T* (astronauts back to the Moon, and someday people may live there. Anyone who does will need to answer very practical ) Tj
T* (questions: How long is a day? How hot does it get? Why must you always wear a suit? This lesson is your astronaut ) Tj
T* (briefing.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**A 'day' means one full spin.** Earth spins around once every 24 hours -- that's why we ) Tj
T* (get a sunrise every morning. The Moon spins too, but **very slowly**: one full day-night cycle on the Moon takes about ) Tj
T* (**29.5 Earth days**.\\n\\nThat means if you stood on the Moon:\\n\\n- **Daytime would last about two weeks.** The Sun would ) Tj
T* (crawl across the sky so slowly you could barely see it move.\\n- **Night would also last about two weeks** -- fourteen ) Tj
T* (Earth-days of darkness.\\n\\n**The sky is black even at noon.** Earth's daytime sky is blue because our **air** scatters ) Tj
T* (sunlight everywhere above us \(a whole lesson awaits you in the Atmosphere world!\). The Moon has **no air at all**. No ) Tj
T* (air means nothing to scatter light -- so the Sun blazes in a perfectly black, star-less-looking sky. Sunlit ground, ) Tj
T* (black sky, all at once.\\n\\nNo air also means:\\n\\n- **No sound.** Sound travels by shaking air. No air, no sound -- ) Tj
T* (astronauts talk by radio.\\n- **No wind and no rain.** Nothing ever blows the dust around. That's why astronaut ) Tj
T* (**footprints from 1969 are still there today**, sharp as the day they were made, and could last millions of years.\\n- ) Tj
T* (**Wild temperatures.** On Earth, air acts like a blanket, spreading warmth around. With no blanket, the Moon's daytime ) Tj
T* (ground roasts to about **120 degC** \(hotter than boiling water\) and its night plunges to about **-130 degC** \(far colder) Tj
T* ( than Antarctica\). Space suits are really wearable air-conditioned blankets.\\n\\nOne last wonder: the Moon spins ) Tj
T* (**exactly** once for every trip it makes around Earth. Because of that perfect match, **the same side of the Moon always) Tj
T* ( faces us**. People on Earth had never seen the far side until a spacecraft flew around and photographed it in 1959!") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SIMULATION",) Tj
