T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "The two-week school day",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A 'school day' on Earth lasts from morning to afternoon -- part of one Earth spin. If ) Tj
T* (you went to school for one whole Moon daytime, about how many Earth days would you be there?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "One full Moon day-night cycle is about 29.5 Earth days.",) Tj
T* (                      "Daytime is about half of that cycle.",) Tj
T* (                      "29.5 / 2 ~= 14.75.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "About 14 to 15 Earth days of nonstop daylight. Pack a very big lunch.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "The silent hammer",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "An astronaut hammers a flag pole into the Moon's surface. Her friend stands ten steps ) Tj
T* (away, watching. What does the friend hear?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Sound needs something to travel through -- usually air.",) Tj
T* (                      "The Moon has no air between the two astronauts.",) Tj
T* (                      "Vibrations from the hammer can't cross the gap \(though the hammering astronaut might feel buzzing) Tj
T* ( through her own suit and bones\).") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Nothing at all. The friend sees the hammer strike in total silence -- that's why suits ) Tj
T* (have radios.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Footprints forever",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "On Earth, a footprint on the beach disappears within hours. Why are 50-year-old ) Tj
T* (footprints on the Moon still perfect?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "On Earth, wind blows sand and rain washes prints away.",) Tj
T* (                      "Wind and rain are made of moving air and water.",) Tj
T* (                      "The Moon has no air and no liquid water -- nothing ever disturbs the dust.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "With no wind, rain, or weather of any kind, nothing erases them. They may last millions ) Tj
T* (of years.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
