T* (                "headline": "Welcome Home",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "You've returned from the Moon to a world where dropped toast hits the floor fast -- and somehow,) Tj
T* ( people in Australia aren't falling off the bottom of the planet.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Everything you do today depends on falling. Pour juice: gravity pulls it into the cup. Take) Tj
T* ( a step: gravity plants your foot back on the ground. Play basketball, ride a bike downhill, watch rain fill a puddle --) Tj
T* ( falling, falling, falling.\\n\\nBut here's a puzzle that confused people for thousands of years. The Earth is a **giant ) Tj
T* (ball**. There are kids in Australia, on the 'other side' of that ball, dropping their toast right now. Why doesn't their) Tj
T* ( toast fall *off* the Earth into space? Why don't *they*?\\n\\nThe answer changes what the word 'down' really means -- and) Tj
T* ( once you see it, you can never unsee it.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "On the Moon you learned that gravity pulls everything **toward the center** of a world. Now) Tj
T* ( we're standing on the biggest world you'll ever live on, so let's take that idea seriously.\\n\\n**'Down' is not a ) Tj
T* (direction in space. 'Down' means 'toward the center of the Earth.'**\\n\\nPicture the Earth as a giant ball with a magnet ) Tj
T* (for *everything* buried at its very center \(it's not a real magnet -- it's gravity -- but the picture helps\). A person ) Tj
T* (in Canada is pulled toward the center. A person in Australia is pulled toward the **same center** -- which, for them, is) Tj
T* ( also toward the ground under their feet. Both feel perfectly right-side-up. There is no 'bottom' of the Earth, because ) Tj
T* (every direction toward the center counts as down.\\n\\n**Earth's pull is strong.** Drop something here and it speeds up ) Tj
T* (fast -- much faster than on the Moon. After one second of falling, a dropped ball is already moving at about **10 meters) Tj
T* ( per second** \(faster than a sprinting champion\). And falling things keep **speeding up** the longer they fall. That's ) Tj
T* (why a fall from a chair is fine, but a fall from a roof is dangerous: more time falling means more speed.\\n\\n**Heavy and) Tj
T* ( light fall together.** This surprises everyone. Drop a big rock and a small rock at the same time: they land ) Tj
T* (**together**. Gravity pulls the heavy one harder, but the heavy one also needs more pull to get moving -- and the two ) Tj
T* (effects exactly cancel out. The only cheater is **air**: a feather or a flat sheet of paper falls slowly because air ) Tj
T* (catches it like a parachute. Crumple the paper into a ball \(same paper, same weight!\) and it drops like a stone. The ) Tj
T* (difference was never the weight -- it was the air.\\n\\nSo your three Earth rules:\\n\\n1. Down = toward Earth's center, ) Tj
T* (everywhere on the planet.\\n2. Falling things speed up as they fall.\\n3. Without air in the way, everything falls ) Tj
T* (together.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
