T* (        {) Tj
T* (          "slug": "pushes-and-pulls",) Tj
T* (          "title": "Pushes and Pulls",) Tj
T* (          "tagline": "Forces -- how everything that moves gets moving",) Tj
T* (          "estMinutes": 12,) Tj
T* (          "xpReward": 100,) Tj
T* (          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "earth",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Make It Move",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "A soccer ball will sit in the grass until the end of time -- unless something pushes it. Meet ) Tj
T* (forces: the pushes and pulls behind every movement on Earth.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Watch a playground for one minute and count the pushes and pulls. A swing is pushed. A ) Tj
T* (wagon is pulled. A ball is kicked \(a push from a foot\), caught \(a pull-to-a-stop by hands\), and thrown again.\\n\\nNothing) Tj
T* ( -- not a ball, not a bike, not a planet -- starts moving, stops moving, or changes direction **by itself**. Something ) Tj
T* (must push or pull it. Scientists call every push and every pull a **force**, and forces are the steering wheel of the ) Tj
T* (entire universe. Even gravity, your old friend from the Moon, is just one famous example of a pull.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**A force is a push or a pull.** Forces are invisible, but you can always see what they ) Tj
T* (*do*. A force can:\\n\\n- **Start** something moving \(kick a resting ball\),\\n- **Stop** something moving \(catch the ) Tj
T* (ball\),\\n- **Speed it up or slow it down** \(pedal harder; squeeze the brakes\),\\n- **Change its direction** \(bat hits ball) Tj
T* ( -- the ball was flying one way and leaves another\),\\n- **Squash or stretch it** \(squeeze clay, stretch a rubber ) Tj
T* (band\).\\n\\n**Bigger force, bigger change.** Tap a toy car and it rolls a little. Shove it and it races. The harder the ) Tj
T* (push, the faster things speed up.\\n\\n**Heavier things are harder to change.** Push an empty shopping cart: easy. Push a ) Tj
T* (full one with the *same strength*: it barely gets going. More stuff \(more **mass**\) means more force is needed for the ) Tj
T* (same change. This is also why a rolling bowling ball is harder to stop than a rolling tennis ball.\\n\\n**The hidden ) Tj
T* (force: friction.** Roll a ball across grass and it slows down and stops -- but you never see anything touch it. ) Tj
T* (Something did: **friction**, a force made wherever two surfaces rub. Friction always pushes *against* sliding. Rough ) Tj
T* (surfaces \(grass, carpet, sandpaper\) make lots of friction; smooth surfaces \(ice, polished floors\) make little. That's ) Tj
T* (why the same hockey puck glides forever on ice but dies quickly on pavement.\\n\\nFriction isn't the enemy, though. ) Tj
T* (**Without friction you couldn't walk** -- your shoes would slip like on perfect ice. Brakes, knots, and even holding a ) Tj
T* (pencil all depend on it.\\n\\nSo whenever anything changes how it's moving, ask the physicist's question: **what pushed or) Tj
T* ( pulled it?** There is always an answer.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SIMULATION",) Tj
ET
