(              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**A magnet is an object that pulls on certain metals** -- mainly **iron** and **steel** ) Tj
T* (\(steel is mostly iron\). Bring a magnet near a paperclip and the clip leaps to it.\\n\\nBut magnets are picky! They ignore ) Tj
T* (plastic, wood, glass, paper, rubber -- and even most metals. A soda can \(aluminum\), a gold ring, a copper coin: no pull ) Tj
T* (at all. **Magnetic != metal.** Only iron-family metals join the club. The test is simple: if a magnet grabs it, there's ) Tj
T* (iron or steel inside.\\n\\n**Every magnet has two ends, called poles:** a **north pole \(N\)** and a **south pole \(S\)**. You) Tj
T* ( can't have one without the other -- snap a magnet in half and each piece instantly has its own N and S!\\n\\nThe poles ) Tj
T* (follow one golden rule:\\n\\n- **Opposite poles attract.** N pulls on S. Click!\\n- **Same poles repel.** N pushes away N; ) Tj
T* (S pushes away S. Try to force them together and you'll feel an invisible springy cushion fighting your fingers.\\n\\nThat ) Tj
T* (repelling push is special -- it's one of the only ways to feel an **invisible push** with your bare hands.\\n\\n**Magnetic) Tj
T* ( force passes through things.** A magnet can hold paper to the fridge because its pull reaches *through* the paper. It ) Tj
T* (works through cardboard, plastic, glass, even your hand. But the force fades fast with distance -- a magnet that snaps ) Tj
T* (up a paperclip from one centimeter away may be helpless from ten.\\n\\n**The biggest magnet you know is under your feet.**) Tj
T* ( Deep inside Earth, churning liquid iron turns our whole planet into a giant \(gentle\) magnet, with magnetic poles near ) Tj
T* (the North and South Poles. A **compass** is just a tiny magnet balanced on a pin -- Earth's magnetism pulls its N end to) Tj
T* ( point north. With that one trick, explorers crossed oceans long before satellites existed.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
