T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Right now, while you read this, it is the middle of the night for kids on the other side of) Tj
T* ( the world. When you eat breakfast, they're sound asleep. When you go to bed, their school day is starting.\\n\\nFor most ) Tj
T* (of human history, people believed the obvious: that the Sun circles around the Earth, rising in the east and setting in ) Tj
T* (the west. It *looks* exactly like that! It took bold thinkers like **Copernicus** and **Galileo** to prove the opposite ) Tj
T* (-- and the real answer explains time zones, sunrises, why your shadow moves, and why 'sunset' is a beautiful illusion.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**The Earth spins.** Our planet rotates around an invisible line through the North and ) Tj
T* (South Poles -- its **axis** -- like a giant carousel, making one complete turn every **24 hours**. You, your house, and ) Tj
T* (your whole country are riders on that carousel, moving right now at hundreds of kilometers per hour. \(You don't feel it ) Tj
T* (because the spin is perfectly smooth -- just as you don't feel speed in a smooth airplane.\)\\n\\n**The Sun, meanwhile, ) Tj
T* (shines steadily** from one direction. And here's the key picture: at any moment, the Sun can only light up **half the ) Tj
T* (ball**. Shine a flashlight on a globe and you'll see it instantly -- one half bright, one half dark. Always.\\n\\n- The ) Tj
T* (half facing the Sun is having **daytime**.\\n- The half facing away is having **night**.\\n\\nAs Earth turns, you ride from) Tj
T* ( the dark half into the bright half. From where you stand, it looks like the Sun is climbing up over the horizon -- we ) Tj
T* (call it **sunrise**, but really it's *you-rise*: your part of Earth is turning to face the Sun. Twelve hours later you ) Tj
T* (ride back into the shadow, and the Sun seems to sink -- **sunset**, or really *you-set*.\\n\\nBecause Earth spins toward ) Tj
T* (the **east**, the Sun always appears to rise in the **east** and set in the **west**, everywhere on the planet.\\n\\nThis ) Tj
T* (also explains **shadows**. In the morning, with the Sun low in the east, your shadow stretches long toward the west. At ) Tj
T* (midday, the Sun is high and your shadow shrinks to a puddle at your feet. By evening it stretches long again -- toward ) Tj
T* (the east this time. Your shadow is a sundial, silently tracking the Earth's turn.\\n\\nAnd remember the Moon world: the ) Tj
T* (Moon makes this same kind of turn, but takes almost a month. Earth's brisk 24-hour spin is why our days feel just right ) Tj
T* (-- and as you'll learn someday, it's no accident life likes it that way.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
