T* (          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "atmosphere",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "You Live Underwater \(Sort Of\)",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "Above your head right now: a column of air 100 kilometers tall, pressing down with the weight of) Tj
T* ( a small car per square meter. Why aren't you crushed?") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Air seems like nothing. You can't see it, can't grab it, walk through it like it isn't ) Tj
T* (there. For most of history, people assumed air weighed nothing at all.\\n\\nThey were spectacularly wrong. Air is ) Tj
T* (**stuff** -- trillions of tiny molecules of nitrogen and oxygen zipping around and bumping into everything. And stuff ) Tj
T* (has **weight**. The entire blanket of air wrapped around Earth -- the **atmosphere** -- weighs about five and a half ) Tj
T* (**quadrillion tonnes**.\\n\\nThat weight explains why your ears pop in elevators and airplanes, why bags of chips puff up ) Tj
T* (on mountain drives, how drinking straws actually work, and why weather forecasters obsess over 'high pressure' and 'low ) Tj
T* (pressure.' Welcome to the bottom of the ocean of air.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Air is matter.** It's made of molecules -- far too small to see, but real. A bedroom's ) Tj
T* (worth of air weighs about as much as a house cat. An empty school gym holds roughly a few hundred kilograms of air. ) Tj
T* ('Empty' is never really empty.\\n\\n**Air pressure is the weight of all the air above you.** Stack books on your hand: ) Tj
T* (each added book presses harder. Now realize the atmosphere is a stack about **100 kilometers tall**, and you're at the ) Tj
T* (bottom. All that air pushes on you with a pressure scientists measure as about **101 kilopascals \(kPa\)** at sea level --) Tj
T* ( roughly **1 kilogram pressing on every square centimeter** of your body, or ten tonnes on a desk!\\n\\n**So why aren't ) Tj
T* (you crushed?** Two reasons. First, air pushes in **all directions** -- down, up, and sideways -- because its molecules ) Tj
T* (fly every which way. The pushes on each side of your hand balance out. Second, the air *inside* you \(lungs, ears, blood\)) Tj
T* ( pushes **outward** with the same pressure. Inside push equals outside push: you feel nothing. You only notice pressure ) Tj
T* (when it gets **unbalanced** -- like when an elevator ride leaves old-pressure air trapped in your ears. The 'pop' is ) Tj
T* (your inner ear equalizing. Equilibrium restored!\\n\\n**Pressure drops as you climb.** Go up a mountain and there's less ) Tj
T* (air left above you, so the stack weighs less. The rule of thumb: pressure roughly **halves every 5.5 km** you ) Tj
T* (climb.\\n\\n- Sea level: ~100 kPa\\n- 5.5 km \(higher than most mountains\): ~50 kPa\\n- 11 km \(airliner cruising height\): ~25) Tj
ET
endstream
