T* (                "scene": "atmosphere",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "The Color of Air",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "The most-asked science question in history has a real answer -- and the same answer explains ) Tj
T* (blue noons, orange sunsets, and the black sky of the Moon.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Every kid on Earth has asked it. Most adults still can't answer it. Yet 'why is the sky ) Tj
T* (blue?' is a real physics question with a beautiful, complete answer -- one that was only nailed down about 150 years ago) Tj
T* ( by the physicist **Lord Rayleigh**.\\n\\nThe answer is bigger than one color. It explains why sunsets glow orange and ) Tj
T* (red, why the Moon's daytime sky is dead black, why distant mountains look hazy and bluish, and even helps explain why ) Tj
T* (Mars has a butterscotch sky. One mechanism, half the beauty in the sky.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Step 1: Sunlight is secretly every color at once.** The Sun's white light is a mixture of) Tj
T* ( all the rainbow's colors -- red, orange, yellow, green, blue, violet -- blended together. A prism \(or raindrops making ) Tj
T* (a rainbow\) can unmix them. Each color is a light wave with a different **wavelength**: red waves are long and lazy; blue) Tj
T* ( and violet waves are short and choppy.\\n\\n**Step 2: Air bumps light around.** The atmosphere is full of molecules ) Tj
T* (\(mostly nitrogen\). When sunlight streams through, the light waves jostle these molecules, and the molecules fling some ) Tj
T* (of the light off in random new directions. This is called **scattering**.\\n\\n**Step 3: Here's the secret -- blue ) Tj
T* (scatters far more than red.** Short, choppy waves get bounced around much more easily than long, lazy ones. Blue light ) Tj
T* (scatters roughly **ten times more** than red light. \(Violet scatters even more, but the Sun sends less violet and our ) Tj
T* (eyes are weak at seeing it -- so blue wins.\)\\n\\n**Put it together:** as sunlight crosses the sky, its blue part gets ) Tj
T* (knocked around the atmosphere again and again, bouncing molecule to molecule, until blue light is raining down on you ) Tj
T* (**from every direction of the sky**. Look anywhere away from the Sun and you see that scattered blue. **The sky is blue ) Tj
T* (because you're seeing sunlight's blue, bounced down to your eyes by the air itself.**\\n\\n**Now the sunset trick.** At ) Tj
T* (noon, sunlight punches almost straight down through the atmosphere -- a short trip. But at sunrise and sunset, the Sun ) Tj
T* (sits on the horizon, and its light must **slice sideways through hundreds of kilometers of air** to reach you -- a ) Tj
T* (journey dozens of times longer. Along that marathon, almost *all* the blue \(and even the green\) gets scattered away to ) Tj
T* (other places, leaving what survives the trip: **orange and red**. The Sun blushes, and clouds catch the leftover ) Tj
T* (fire.\\n\\n**Final proof: remove the air.** No air, no scattering, no color. On the Moon -- as you saw in World 1 -- the ) Tj
T* (Sun blazes in a pitch-black daytime sky. Astronauts orbiting Earth watch our thin glowing blue rim from above: the ) Tj
T* (atmosphere itself, doing its scattering trick, visible from space.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SIMULATION",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Try it: sunset machine",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
