(thing. A wing is a machine for organizing that shove.\\n\\n**Four forces wrestle over every plane:**\\n\\n- **Weight** -- ) Tj
T* (gravity pulling the plane down \(old friend!\).\\n- **Lift** -- the upward push from air on the wings.\\n- **Thrust** -- ) Tj
T* (engines pushing the plane forward.\\n- **Drag** -- air resistance pulling backward \(the same force that slowed your flat ) Tj
T* (sheet of paper\).\\n\\nTo fly level, **lift must equal weight**. To hold speed, **thrust must equal drag**. Flying is a ) Tj
T* (balancing act between these four, every second.\\n\\n**So where does lift come from?** Two views of the same ) Tj
T* (deal:\\n\\n**View 1 -- the push-back \(Newton\).** A wing is tilted and shaped so that, as it slices forward, it **deflects ) Tj
T* (huge amounts of air downward** -- both off its bottom surface and by pulling air down along its curved top. And remember) Tj
T* ( the rule from Pushes and Pulls: *every push gets a push back.* The wing throws air **down**; the air throws the wing ) Tj
T* (**up**. A big airliner's wings hurl tonnes of air downward every second -- that's the upward shove holding 500 tonnes ) Tj
T* (aloft.\\n\\n**View 2 -- the pressure difference \(Bernoulli\).** Air sweeping over the wing's curved top moves faster than ) Tj
T* (the air below, and faster-moving air presses more weakly. Result: **strong pressure below, weak pressure above** -- a ) Tj
T* (net upward squeeze. Try it yourself: hold a strip of paper to your lips, drooping down, and blow hard across its ) Tj
T* (**top**. The strip rises! You weakened the pressure above it, and the still air below pushed it up.\\n\\nBoth views are ) Tj
T* (correct -- they're two descriptions of one event: the wing organizing the air.\\n\\n**The two levers of lift:** go ) Tj
T* (**faster** \(more air handled per second -- this is why planes need long runways to build speed before lifting off\) or ) Tj
T* (meet **more air** \(bigger wings, or thicker air\). Which explains two famous facts: planes climbing into the thin air at ) Tj
T* (11 km must fly far faster to grip enough air... and on the airless Moon, no wing, propeller, or helicopter can work *at ) Tj
T* (all*. Rockets only fly there because they bring their own push -- throwing fuel down instead of air.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
