T* (        "glow": "#2A6FB8") Tj
T* (      },) Tj
T* (      "lessons": [) Tj
T* (        {) Tj
T* (          "slug": "forces-and-motion-basics",) Tj
T* (          "title": "Forces: Pushes and Pulls",) Tj
T* (          "tagline": "Every change in motion starts with a force",) Tj
T* (          "estMinutes": 15,) Tj
T* (          "xpReward": 120,) Tj
T* (          "difficulty": 2,) Tj
T* (          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "atmosphere",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "What Moves the Movers?",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "300 km up, astronauts float as if weightless. A single fingertip push sends one drifting across ) Tj
T* (the cabin. Up here, with friction nearly gone, the real rules of force finally show themselves.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Why does a kicked ball eventually stop, but a spacecraft coasts for years? Why is it hard ) Tj
T* (to start a heavy cart moving -- and just as hard to stop it once it's rolling?\\n\\nThe answer to every one of these is ) Tj
T* (**force**: a push or a pull. Forces start motion, stop motion, speed things up, slow them down, and turn them. Learn how) Tj
T* ( forces work and you can explain a soccer kick, a seatbelt, a rocket launch, and the drift of an astronaut all with the ) Tj
T* (same handful of ideas.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**A force is a push or a pull.** We measure force in **newtons \(N\)**. Holding a small apple) Tj
T* ( takes about 1 N. Forces have a **size** and a **direction** -- a 10 N push north is different from a 10 N push ) Tj
T* (south.\\n\\n**Forces add up.** Two people pushing a box the same way combine their forces. Pushing opposite ways, they ) Tj
T* (subtract. The single force left over after all the pushes and pulls are combined is the **net force** $F_{net}$.\\n\\n- ) Tj
T* (**Balanced forces** \($F_{net} = 0$\): the pushes cancel. The object keeps doing exactly what it was doing -- staying ) Tj
T* (still, or moving at steady speed in a straight line.\\n- **Unbalanced forces** \($F_{net} \\\\ne 0$\): there's a leftover ) Tj
T* (push. Now -- and only now -- the motion **changes**: it speeds up, slows down, or turns.\\n\\n**This is the great idea of ) Tj
T* (inertia.** Objects resist changes to their motion. A still object stays still; a moving object keeps moving -- *unless ) Tj
T* (an unbalanced force acts on it*. So a ball doesn't 'naturally' stop. Something stops it: the unbalanced forces of ) Tj
T* (**friction** and air resistance, quietly pushing backward. Remove them, and motion never quits -- which is exactly why a) Tj
T* ( spacecraft coasts across the solar system and an astronaut drifts until a wall pushes back.\\n\\n**More force, or less ) Tj
T* (mass, means a bigger change.** Push the same cart harder and it speeds up faster. Load the cart with bricks \(more ) Tj
T* (**mass**\) and the same push barely budges it. Heavy things have more inertia -- they resist changes more ) Tj
T* (stubbornly.\\n\\n**Every push comes with a push back.** Push off a wall while floating in space and *you* shoot backward ) Tj
T* (-- the wall pushed you exactly as hard as you pushed it. Forces always come in pairs, in opposite directions. A rocket ) Tj
T* (throws gas downward; the gas throws the rocket up. A swimmer pushes water back; the water pushes the swimmer forward.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Tug-of-war net force",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "The red team pulls a rope left with 400 N. The blue team pulls right with 350 N. What is) Tj
T* ( the net force, and which way does the rope move?",) Tj
