T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "atmosphere",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Lift Ten Times Your Weight",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "The Space Station's robotic arm moves multi-tonne modules with a gentle motor. Its secret is the) Tj
T* ( same one behind a seesaw, a ramp, and a bottle opener: the simple machine.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "How did ancient builders raise stone blocks heavier than houses? How does a small child ) Tj
T* (lift a grown adult on a seesaw? How can one arm crank a car up off the ground?\\n\\nNone of it breaks the rules of force ) Tj
T* (-- it **reroutes** them. A **simple machine** lets a small force do a big job, by spreading that force over a longer ) Tj
T* (distance. Ramps, levers, pulleys, and wheels are the building blocks of every complex machine ever made, from a ) Tj
T* (wheelbarrow to a robotic arm in orbit.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**A simple machine changes a force** -- its size, its direction, or both -- to make a task ) Tj
T* (easier.\\n\\n**The deal you can't escape:** machines don't give you free energy. They let you push with **less force**, ) Tj
T* (but you must push over a **longer distance** to make up for it. Force down, distance up. \(You'll see exactly why in the ) Tj
T* (next lesson on work.\)\\n\\n**Mechanical advantage \(MA\)** measures the help: how many times bigger the output force is than) Tj
T* ( the force you put in.\\n\\n$$MA = \\\\frac{\\\\text{output force \(load\)}}{\\\\text{input force \(effort\)}}$$\\n\\nAn MA of 4 means) Tj
T* ( you push with 1 unit and get 4 units of lifting force -- but you'll pull 4 times as far.\\n\\n**The classic simple ) Tj
T* (machines:**\\n\\n- **Lever** -- a bar that pivots on a **fulcrum**. Push down far from the fulcrum to lift a big load ) Tj
T* (close to it. Seesaws, crowbars, scissors, and your forearm are levers.\\n- **Inclined plane \(ramp\)** -- instead of ) Tj
T* (lifting a load straight up, push it up a gentle slope. Less force, longer path. Wheelchair ramps and mountain switchback) Tj
T* ( roads.\\n- **Pulley** -- a grooved wheel with a rope. One fixed pulley just changes direction \(pull down to lift up\). ) Tj
T* (Add more pulleys and you split the load across several rope sections, multiplying your force.\\n- **Wheel and axle** -- a) Tj
T* ( big wheel turning a small axle \(or vice-versa\). Steering wheels, doorknobs, and winches.\\n- **Wedge** -- two ramps ) Tj
T* (back-to-back that move; it splits or cuts. Axes, knives, and your front teeth.\\n- **Screw** -- a ramp wrapped around a ) Tj
T* (cylinder; it converts turning into a strong straight pull. Jar lids, bolts, and drills.\\n\\n**Friction takes a cut.** ) Tj
T* (Real machines lose some effort to friction as heat, so the actual help is always a little less than the ideal. Oiling a ) Tj
T* (machine reduces friction and recovers some of that lost effort.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
ET
endstream
