T* (                "scene": "atmosphere",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Hold a Crate All Day, Do Zero Work",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "In physics, straining to hold a heavy box that doesn't move counts as no work at all. The ) Tj
T* (definition is strict -- and once you know it, energy starts to make sense.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "'Work' in everyday life means anything tiring. In physics it means something precise: a ) Tj
T* (**force moving an object through a distance**. This sharp definition is the bridge between forces \(last lessons\) and ) Tj
T* (**energy** \(next lesson\).\\n\\nAnd **power** -- how *fast* you do work -- is why we rate engines, light bulbs, and rockets) Tj
T* ( in watts and horsepower. Get these two ideas and you can compare a sprinter to an elevator to a Saturn V rocket on the ) Tj
T* (same scale.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Work means a force makes something move.** In physics:\\n\\n$$W = F \\\\times d$$\\n\\nWork $W$) Tj
T* ( \(in **joules, J**\) equals the force $F$ \(in newtons\) times the distance $d$ \(in meters\) the object moves **in the ) Tj
