(direction of the force**. One joule is one newton pushing through one meter.\\n\\n**The strict part:** if nothing moves, ) Tj
T* (**no work is done**, no matter how hard you strain. Holding a heavy box still: $d = 0$, so $W = 0$. Pushing a wall that ) Tj
T* (won't budge: zero work. Carrying a box across a flat room: the lifting force is *upward* but the motion is *sideways*, ) Tj
T* (so that force does no work either. Work needs motion **along the force**.\\n\\n**Work is the transfer of energy.** When ) Tj
T* (you do work on something, you give it energy -- you speed it up, or lift it higher. That's why work and energy share the) Tj
T* ( same unit, the joule. \(This is the secret behind simple machines: they can't change the work needed, only split it into) Tj
T* ( a smaller force over a longer distance -- same $F \\\\times d$.\)\\n\\n**Power is how fast you do work:**\\n\\n$$P = ) Tj
T* (\\\\frac{W}{t}$$\\n\\nPower $P$ \(in **watts, W**\) is work divided by the time $t$ taken. One watt is one joule per second. ) Tj
T* (Run up the stairs and you do the same work as walking up -- but in less time, so more power. A 100 W bulb uses 100 ) Tj
T* (joules every second. A car engine might deliver tens of thousands of watts; a rocket, billions.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Work lifting a box",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "You lift a 50 N box straight up onto a shelf 2 m high. How much work do you do?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Use $W = F \\\\times d$ with the force and the distance along it.",) Tj
T* (                      "$W = 50 \\\\times 2$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$= 100$ J.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "100 joules -- and that energy is now stored in the box as height \(potential energy\), ) Tj
T* (ready to be released if it falls.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "The strict definition",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A waiter carries a 20 N tray steadily across a level room, 8 m. How much work does the ) Tj
T* (carrying force do on the tray?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "The supporting force points up; the tray moves sideways.",) Tj
T* (                      "Work counts only motion in the direction of the force.",) Tj
T* (                      "There is no motion along the upward force, so $d = 0$ for that force.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Zero work \(on the tray, by the lifting force\). Tiring, yes -- but physics work needs ) Tj
T* (motion along the force, and here there is none.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Same work, more power",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Two students each do 600 J of work climbing a staircase. Ana takes 10 s; Ben takes 5 s. ) Tj
T* (Who is more powerful, and by how much?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Power is work over time: $P = W / t$.",) Tj
T* (                      "Ana: $600 / 10 = 60$ W.",) Tj
T* (                      "Ben: $600 / 5 = 120$ W.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Ben, at 120 W versus Ana's 60 W -- double the power for the same work, because he did it ) Tj
