(            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "atmosphere",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "The Wave That Crosses an Ocean",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "A wave can travel thousands of kilometers, yet the water barely moves -- it just bobs up and ) Tj
T* (down. Waves carry energy, not stuff. That single idea explains sound, light, and earthquakes.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Drop a pebble in a pond and rings spread outward. Shout, and your voice reaches a friend. ) Tj
T* (Flip on a lamp and light fills the room. Earthquakes shake whole cities from kilometers away.\\n\\nAll four are **waves** ) Tj
T* (-- and they share the same rules. A wave is how **energy travels from place to place without matter making the whole ) Tj
T* (journey**. Learn the anatomy of a wave once, and you've started to understand sound, light, music, radio, and the ) Tj
T* (telescopes that read the universe.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**A wave carries energy, not matter.** Watch a duck on rippling water: the ripples race ) Tj
T* (past, but the duck just bobs **up and down** in place. The water doesn't travel to shore -- the *wave* does, passing its) Tj
T* ( energy along.\\n\\n**Two types of wave:**\\n\\n- **Transverse** -- the material wiggles *across* the direction the wave ) Tj
T* (travels. Water ripples, a shaken rope, and light are transverse.\\n- **Longitudinal** -- the material squashes and ) Tj
T* (stretches *along* the direction of travel. Sound is longitudinal: air gets pushed into compressions and pulled into ) Tj
T* (gaps.\\n\\n**The anatomy of a wave:**\\n\\n- **Amplitude** -- how big the wiggle is \(the height of a crest\). Bigger ) Tj
T* (amplitude means **more energy** -- a louder sound, a brighter light, a taller ocean wave.\\n- **Wavelength** \($\\\\lambda$\)) Tj
T* ( -- the distance from one crest to the next.\\n- **Frequency** \($f$\) -- how many waves pass each second, measured in ) Tj
T* (**hertz \(Hz\)**. High frequency means crests arrive quickly.\\n- **Wave speed** \($v$\) -- how fast the wave ) Tj
T* (travels.\\n\\n**The wave equation ties them together:**\\n\\n$$v = f \\\\times \\\\lambda$$\\n\\nSpeed equals frequency times ) Tj
T* (wavelength. For a fixed speed, squeezing the wavelength shorter forces the frequency higher, and vice-versa. This one ) Tj
T* (relationship runs through everything that follows: a high musical note is a high frequency; a short-wavelength light ) Tj
T* (wave is high frequency too.\\n\\n**Waves bounce, bend, and blend.** They **reflect** off barriers \(an echo\), **refract** ) Tj
T* (\(bend\) when they pass into a new material at an angle, and **interfere** when they overlap -- crests adding to crests ) Tj
T* (\(louder/brighter\) or crests filling troughs \(silence/darkness\). These behaviors are the fingerprints that tell ) Tj
T* (scientists they're looking at a wave at all.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Using the wave equation",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A wave on a rope has a frequency of 4 Hz and a wavelength of 0.5 m. How fast does it ) Tj
T* (travel?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Use $v = f \\\\times \\\\lambda$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$v = 4 \\\\times 0.5$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$= 2$ m/s.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "2 m/s. Four waves per second, each half a meter long, march past at two meters every ) Tj
T* (second.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Bigger amplitude, more energy",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Two ocean waves have the same wavelength, but wave A is twice as tall as wave B. Which ) Tj
T* (carries more energy, and what changed?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Amplitude is the height of the wave.",) Tj
T* (                      "Energy increases with amplitude.",) Tj
T* (                      "Wave A's greater height means greater amplitude.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Wave A carries more energy. Taller waves \(greater amplitude\) carry more energy -- which ) Tj
T* (is why a big wave hits harder than a ripple of the same length.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "The bobbing duck",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A wave travels across a lake toward the shore. Does the water itself travel to the ) Tj
T* (shore? What does?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "A floating duck shows the water's true motion: up and down in place.",) Tj
T* (                      "The crests move forward, but the water returns to where it started.",) Tj
T* (                      "What moves forward is the wave's energy.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "The water mostly stays put, bobbing up and down; the wave \(energy\) is what travels to ) Tj
T* (shore. Waves move energy, not matter.") Tj
ET
