(          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "atmosphere",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "In Space, No One Can Hear You",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "A rocket launch is one of the loudest sounds on Earth -- yet the same engines firing in deep ) Tj
T* (space make no sound at all. Sound needs something to travel through, and space is empty.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Music, speech, a warning siren, a doctor's ultrasound, a bat hunting in the dark -- all are) Tj
T* ( **sound**. Sound is how we communicate, enjoy music, and even peer inside the human body and the ocean floor.\\n\\nAnd ) Tj
T* (the rule that sound needs a **medium** explains one of the strangest facts about space: it's utterly silent. Master ) Tj
T* (sound and you'll understand pitch, loudness, echoes, sonic booms, and why the movies get space battles completely ) Tj
T* (wrong.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Sound is a vibration travelling through a material.** Pluck a guitar string and it shakes) Tj
T* ( the air next to it, squeezing the air into **compressions** and **rarefactions** \(gaps\) that ripple outward -- a ) Tj
T* (longitudinal wave. Those pulses reach your eardrum, vibrate it, and your brain hears 'sound.'\\n\\n**Sound needs a ) Tj
T* (medium.** Air, water, steel -- anything with particles to pass the vibration along. With no particles, there's nothing ) Tj
T* (to vibrate. **In the vacuum of space, sound cannot travel at all.** That's real: outside a spacecraft, the loudest ) Tj
T* (engine is silent.\\n\\n**Two properties you hear:**\\n\\n- **Pitch** \(how high or low\) comes from **frequency**. Fast ) Tj
T* (vibrations \(high frequency\) sound high, like a whistle; slow vibrations \(low frequency\) sound low, like a bass drum. ) Tj
T* (Humans hear roughly 20 Hz to 20,000 Hz. Below that is *infrasound* \(elephants, earthquakes\); above is *ultrasound* ) Tj
T* (\(bats, medical scanners\).\\n- **Loudness** comes from **amplitude**. Bigger vibrations carry more energy and sound ) Tj
T* (louder. Loudness is measured in **decibels \(dB\)**.\\n\\n**Sound has a speed -- and it's not light's.** In air, sound ) Tj
T* (travels about **343 m/s** \(roughly a kilometer every three seconds\). That's why you see lightning, then hear thunder ) Tj
T* (seconds later: light arrives almost instantly, sound lags behind. Sound actually travels **faster in denser, stiffer ) Tj
T* (materials** -- quicker in water than air, and faster still in steel. Put your ear to a rail and you'll hear a far-off ) Tj
T* (train through the metal before it reaches you through the air.\\n\\n**Beat the speed of sound and you get a sonic boom.** ) Tj
T* (When a jet flies faster than 343 m/s, it outruns its own sound waves, which pile up into a shock wave heard on the ) Tj
T* (ground as a thunderous crack.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "How far is the storm?",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "You see a lightning flash and hear the thunder 6 seconds later. Sound travels about 343 ) Tj
T* (m/s. Roughly how far away was the strike?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Light arrives almost instantly, so the 6 s is sound's travel time.",) Tj
T* (                      "Distance = speed x time = $343 \\\\times 6$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$\\\\approx 2058$ m, about 2 km.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "About 2 kilometers away. A handy rule: every 3 seconds of delay is roughly 1 km.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "High note or low note?",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A singer raises the frequency of the note she's holding. Does the pitch go up or down, ) Tj
T* (and does the speed of the sound in the room change?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Pitch is set by frequency: higher frequency, higher pitch.",) Tj
T* (                      "Raising the frequency raises the pitch.",) Tj
T* (                      "Sound speed depends on the medium \(the air\), not the note -- so it stays about 343 m/s.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "The pitch goes up; the speed of sound stays the same. In a fixed medium, only frequency ) Tj
T* (and wavelength trade off \(v = f lambda\).") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Silence in space",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A movie shows a spaceship exploding with a huge BOOM. What's wrong with this, ) Tj
T* (physically?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Sound is a vibration that needs particles to travel through.",) Tj
T* (                      "Space is a near-perfect vacuum -- almost no particles.",) Tj
T* (                      "With no medium, the vibration can't propagate.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "There would be no sound. In the vacuum of space, explosions are silent -- the movie boom ) Tj
T* (is artistic license, not physics.") Tj
ET
