T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Almost everything you know about the world arrives as **light** entering your eyes. Light ) Tj
T* (lets you see, plants eat, cameras capture, and telescopes reach across the universe to look billions of years into the ) Tj
T* (past.\\n\\nUnderstanding how light **travels in straight lines, reflects, and refracts** explains mirrors, shadows, ) Tj
T* (rainbows, lenses, eyeglasses, cameras, microscopes, and the great space telescopes. It's the physics of seeing itself.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Light travels in straight lines** \(called rays\) until something stops or turns it. That's) Tj
T* ( why a blocked light makes a sharp **shadow**, and why you can't see around corners.\\n\\n**Light is incredibly fast:** ) Tj
T* (about **300,000,000 m/s** in space -- fast enough to circle the Earth 7 times in one second. Nothing travels faster. ) Tj
T* (Because the speed is finite, the light from distant stars is old: we see them as they were long ago.\\n\\n**Three things ) Tj
T* (light does when it meets a surface:**\\n\\n- **Reflection** -- it bounces. A mirror reflects so cleanly you see an image. ) Tj
T* (The rule: the angle coming in equals the angle going out. Rough surfaces scatter light every which way, which is how you) Tj
T* ( see ordinary objects.\\n- **Refraction** -- it **bends** when it passes from one material into another \(air into water, ) Tj
T* (say\) because it changes speed. This is why a straw in a glass looks broken at the surface, and why a pool looks ) Tj
T* (shallower than it is.\\n- **Absorption** -- it's soaked up and turned to heat. A black shirt absorbs most light \(and ) Tj
T* (warms up\); a white shirt reflects most.\\n\\n**Lenses bend light to form images.** A lens is shaped glass that refracts ) Tj
T* (light in a controlled way:\\n\\n- A **convex** \(bulging\) lens bends parallel light rays together to a **focal point**. It ) Tj
T* (can magnify and is the heart of magnifying glasses, cameras, the human eye, and telescopes.\\n- A **concave** \(hollow\) ) Tj
T* (lens spreads rays apart.\\n\\n**Your eye is an optical instrument.** Its lens focuses light onto the retina at the back. ) Tj
T* (If the focus lands a bit short or long, the world looks blurry -- and **eyeglasses add a lens** to fix exactly where the) Tj
T* ( light converges. **Telescopes and microscopes** use the same lens physics, just scaled to gather faint, distant light ) Tj
T* (or magnify the tiny.\\n\\n**Curved mirrors do it too.** The biggest telescopes don't use lenses at all -- they use giant ) Tj
T* (**curved mirrors** to collect and focus starlight, because a huge mirror is far easier to build than a huge lens.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
