T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "atmosphere",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "The Colors You Can't See",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "Radio, microwaves, infrared, X-rays, gamma rays -- all are 'light', just at wavelengths your ) Tj
T* (eyes can't catch. Telescopes built to see them have revealed an invisible universe.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Your phone, the microwave oven, the TV remote, a hospital X-ray, the warmth of a fire -- ) Tj
T* (every one of these uses **light your eyes cannot see**. Visible light is just a narrow band of a vast family of waves ) Tj
T* (called the **electromagnetic spectrum**.\\n\\nLearning the spectrum explains color, why sunscreen matters, how Wi-Fi ) Tj
T* (works, how night-vision cameras see heat, and why astronomers build separate telescopes for radio, infrared, and X-rays.) Tj
T* ( It's the user manual for light in all its forms.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**All these waves are the same thing -- electromagnetic waves -- differing only in ) Tj
T* (wavelength and frequency.** They all travel at the speed of light. Lined up from longest wavelength \(lowest frequency, ) Tj
T* (lowest energy\) to shortest \(highest frequency, highest energy\):\\n\\n**Radio -> Microwave -> Infrared -> Visible -> ) Tj
T* (Ultraviolet -> X-ray -> Gamma ray**\\n\\n- **Radio** -- longest waves; carry broadcast, Wi-Fi, and signals from ) Tj
T* (spacecraft.\\n- **Microwave** -- heat water in food; also carry phone and radar signals.\\n- **Infrared \(IR\)** -- felt as ) Tj
T* (**heat**; TV remotes and night-vision cameras use it.\\n- **Visible light** -- the thin slice your eyes detect, from ) Tj
T* (**red** \(longest visible wavelength\) through orange, yellow, green, blue, to **violet** \(shortest\).\\n- **Ultraviolet ) Tj
T* (\(UV\)** -- just past violet; gives sunburns. The ozone layer blocks most.\\n- **X-rays** -- short, energetic; pass through) Tj
T* ( soft tissue but not bone, so we image skeletons.\\n- **Gamma rays** -- shortest, most energetic; from nuclear reactions ) Tj
T* (and the most violent events in space.\\n\\n**Shorter wavelength means higher frequency and more energy.** That's why gamma) Tj
T* ( rays and X-rays are dangerous \(high energy\) while radio waves pass through you harmlessly.\\n\\n**Color is your eye ) Tj
T* (reading visible wavelengths.** An object looks red because it **reflects red wavelengths** and absorbs the rest; a leaf ) Tj
T* (looks green because it reflects green. A black object absorbs nearly all visible light; a white one reflects nearly all.) Tj
T* ( Mixing the colors of light back together gives white -- which is why sunlight, containing them all, looks ) Tj
T* (white.\\n\\n**The invisible universe.** Earth's atmosphere blocks most UV, X-rays, and gamma rays -- good for life, hard ) Tj
T* (for astronomy. So we launch space telescopes that see in **infrared** \(peering through dust to newborn stars\), **X-ray**) Tj
T* ( \(catching gas swirling into black holes\), and more. Each band of the spectrum reveals things the others can't. Combine ) Tj
T* (them and you get the full picture of the cosmos.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
