T* (                "headline": "+120  degC in Sun, -150  degC in Shadow",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "On the airless Moon, the sunlit ground bakes hotter than boiling water while the shadow beside ) Tj
T* (it freezes colder than Antarctica. Temperature is stranger -- and simpler -- than it seems.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Cooking, weather, climate, engines, refrigerators, spacecraft design -- all are about ) Tj
T* (**heat**. But two everyday words get mixed up constantly: **temperature** and **heat** are not the same thing.\\n\\nGet ) Tj
T* (the difference straight and suddenly you understand why a tiny spark can be hotter than a warm bath yet carry far less ) Tj
T* (energy, why metal feels colder than wood at the same temperature, and what scientists mean by 'absolute zero,' the ) Tj
T* (coldest anything can ever be.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Everything is made of jiggling particles.** Atoms and molecules are always in motion -- ) Tj
T* (vibrating, bouncing, zipping. This particle motion is the key to heat.\\n\\n**Temperature measures the *average* motion of) Tj
T* ( the particles.** Hotter means the particles are moving faster on average; colder means slower. We measure it in ) Tj
T* (**degrees Celsius \( degC\)**, where water freezes at 0 and boils at 100.\\n\\n**Thermal energy is the *total* energy of all) Tj
T* ( the particles' motion.** This depends on temperature **and** on how many particles there are. Here's the crucial ) Tj
T* (difference:\\n\\n- A **lit sparkler** is over 1000  degC -- super-fast particles -- but there are very few of them, so it ) Tj
T* (holds little thermal energy. The sparks land on your skin harmlessly.\\n- A **warm bath** is only 40  degC -- slower ) Tj
T* (particles -- but there are trillions upon trillions of them, so the *total* thermal energy is enormous. It would scald ) Tj
T* (you to stay in boiling water.\\n\\nHigh temperature, low total energy \(spark\). Low temperature, high total energy \(bath\). ) Tj
T* (Temperature is the *average*; thermal energy is the *grand total*.\\n\\n**Heat is thermal energy on the move.** 'Heat' ) Tj
T* (properly means thermal energy **flowing** from a hotter object to a colder one. Heat always flows **hot -> cold**, never) Tj
T* ( the reverse on its own. Hold an ice cube and heat flows from your warm hand into the ice \(which is why your hand feels ) Tj
T* (cold\) -- not 'cold flowing into your hand.' Cold is just the absence of thermal energy.\\n\\n**There's a coldest possible ) Tj
T* (temperature.** Cool something and its particles slow down. Slow them as much as physically possible -- to a near ) Tj
ET
endstream
endobj
