(              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "sun",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Ice, Water, Steam -- Same Stuff",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "Add or remove energy and matter transforms: a glacier, an ocean, and a cloud are all the same ) Tj
T* (molecule wearing different states. The Sun itself is a fourth state you rarely meet.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Water freezing into ice, puddles drying up, a kettle steaming, dry ice fogging a stage -- ) Tj
T* (these are **changes of state**, and they're happening everywhere, all the time. They shape weather, cooking, the water ) Tj
T* (cycle, and the engines that power our world.\\n\\nUnderstanding states of matter -- and the energy it takes to switch ) Tj
T* (between them -- explains why sweating cools you, why steam burns worse than boiling water, and why most of the visible ) Tj
T* (universe is actually made of a state you almost never see on Earth: plasma.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**The state of matter depends on how its particles are arranged and how fast they ) Tj
T* (move.**\\n\\n- **Solid** -- particles packed tightly in a fixed pattern, only vibrating in place. Fixed shape and volume ) Tj
T* (\(ice, rock, metal\).\\n- **Liquid** -- particles still close but free to slide past each other. Fixed volume, but takes ) Tj
T* (the shape of its container \(water, oil\).\\n- **Gas** -- particles far apart, zooming freely. No fixed shape or volume; it) Tj
T* ( fills whatever space it's in \(steam, air\).\\n- **Plasma** -- a super-heated gas whose atoms have been torn apart into ) Tj
T* (charged pieces. It glows and responds to magnetism. Rare on Earth \(lightning, neon signs\) but the **most common state in) Tj
T* ( the universe**: stars, including the Sun, are giant balls of plasma.\\n\\n**Adding energy moves you 'up' \(solid -> liquid) Tj
T* ( -> gas -> plasma\); removing it moves you 'down.'** The named changes:\\n\\n- **Melting** \(solid -> liquid\) and ) Tj
T* (**freezing** \(liquid -> solid\).\\n- **Boiling/evaporation** \(liquid -> gas\) and **condensation** \(gas -> liquid\).\\n- ) Tj
T* (**Sublimation** -- solid straight to gas, skipping liquid \(dry ice, and ice on a freezing-cold dry day\).\\n\\n**The ) Tj
T* (surprising part: during a change of state, the temperature holds steady.** When ice is melting, all the added energy ) Tj
T* (goes into *breaking the particles loose* from their fixed pattern, not into speeding them up -- so an ice-water mix ) Tj
T* (stays at 0  degC until the last ice melts. This 'hidden' energy is called **latent heat**.\\n\\n**This is why steam burns ) Tj
T* (worse than boiling water.** Steam carries all the extra energy that was poured in to turn water into gas. When it ) Tj
T* (touches your skin and condenses back to liquid, it dumps that whole load of latent heat into you -- far more than the ) Tj
T* (same mass of 100  degC water. The same principle, run in reverse, is why **sweating cools you**: evaporating sweat ) Tj
T* (carries energy away from your skin as it turns to gas.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Naming the change",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Name the change of state: \(a\) a puddle disappearing on a sunny day, \(b\) dew forming on ) Tj
T* (grass overnight, \(c\) dry ice 'smoking' without melting.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Puddle to invisible vapor: liquid -> gas.",) Tj
T* (                      "Water vapor in air becoming liquid droplets: gas -> liquid.",) Tj
T* (                      "Solid carbon dioxide turning straight to gas: solid -> gas.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "\(a\) evaporation, \(b\) condensation, \(c\) sublimation. Adding energy drives \(a\) and \(c\); ) Tj
T* (removing it drives \(b\).") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "The melting plateau",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "You heat a beaker of ice-water steadily. While ice is still melting, the temperature ) Tj
T* (won't rise above 0  degC. Where is the energy going?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Added energy can speed particles up \(temperature\) or break their arrangement \(state change\).",) Tj
T* (                      "During melting, it goes into breaking ice's rigid structure.",) Tj
T* (                      "Only once all the ice has melted does added energy start raising the temperature.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Into latent heat -- breaking the solid structure apart. The temperature stays at 0  degC ) Tj
T* (until the last ice melts, then climbs again.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Why steam is dangerous",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Both are at 100  degC, yet steam burns far worse than boiling water. Why?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Turning water to steam required pouring in latent heat.",) Tj
T* (                      "Steam carries that extra energy.",) Tj
T* (                      "Landing on skin, it condenses and releases all that latent heat into you.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Steam holds a large amount of latent heat from boiling. Condensing on your skin, it ) Tj
T* (releases that energy as well as its 100  degC heat, causing a worse burn.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
T* (                ]) Tj
