T* (        {) Tj
T* (          "slug": "energy-heat-efficiency",) Tj
T* (          "title": "Energy, Heat, and Efficiency",) Tj
T* (          "tagline": "Why every machine leaks heat -- and nothing is ever perfect",) Tj
T* (          "estMinutes": 16,) Tj
T* (          "xpReward": 140,) Tj
T* (          "difficulty": 4,) Tj
T* (          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "sun",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "The Tax on Every Transformation",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "Energy is never lost -- yet every engine, bulb, and body pays a 'heat tax' that can never be ) Tj
T* (fully refunded. This one-way leak is among the deepest laws in physics.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why does this matter?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "You learned that energy is conserved -- never created or destroyed. So why do engineers ) Tj
T* (obsess over **efficiency**? Why does a phone get warm? Why can't we build a machine that runs forever?\\n\\nThe answer is ) Tj
T* (that while energy's *total* is conserved, in every real transformation some always escapes as **low-grade heat** that ) Tj
T* (spreads out and becomes hard to use again. Understanding this 'heat tax' is the key to engines, power plants, climate, ) Tj
T* (and why **perpetual motion is impossible**.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Two laws of energy, working together:**\\n\\n**Law 1 -- energy is conserved.** The total ) Tj
T* (amount never changes; it only transforms \(you saw this with kinetic, potential, chemical, and the rest\).\\n\\n**Law 2 -- ) Tj
T* (energy spreads out, and some always becomes waste heat.** In every real transformation, a portion of the energy turns ) Tj
T* (into low-grade **thermal energy** that disperses into the surroundings. It's still 'there' -- total energy is conserved ) Tj
T* (-- but it's spread too thin to do useful work. Heat is the universe's tax collector, and the tax always gets ) Tj
T* (paid.\\n\\n**Efficiency measures how much of the input energy did the useful job:**\\n\\n$$\\\\text{efficiency} = ) Tj
T* (\\\\frac{\\\\text{useful energy out}}{\\\\text{total energy in}} \\\\times 100\\\\%$$\\n\\n- An old incandescent bulb turns only ) Tj
T* (about **10%** of its electrical energy into light -- the other **90%** is wasted heat \(they're warm to the touch!\). LED ) Tj
T* (bulbs reach **80-90%**, which is why they've taken over.\\n- A car engine is roughly **25-30%** efficient; most of the ) Tj
T* (fuel's energy roars away as heat through the exhaust and radiator.\\n- A human body is about **25%** efficient at turning) Tj
T* ( food energy into motion -- the rest keeps you warm \(handy in winter!\).\\n\\n**Efficiency is always less than 100%.** No ) Tj
T* (real machine can turn *all* its input into useful output, because some always escapes as heat. This is exactly why a ) Tj
T* (**perpetual motion machine is impossible**: it would have to recycle energy with no losses forever, and the heat tax ) Tj
T* (forbids it. Every 'free energy' machine ever proposed quietly breaks this law.\\n\\n**The deep idea -- entropy.** Energy ) Tj
T* (naturally flows from concentrated and useful \(the chemical energy in fuel\) toward spread-out and useless \(warmth ) Tj
T* (dispersed into the air\). This one-way drift toward disorder is called **entropy**, and its steady increase even points ) Tj
T* (the **arrow of time**: you can unscramble nothing for free. Improving efficiency means fighting this drift -- capturing ) Tj
T* (more useful energy before the tax takes its cut.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Calculating efficiency",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A motor takes in 500 J of electrical energy and delivers 350 J of useful mechanical ) Tj
T* (energy. What is its efficiency?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Use efficiency = useful out / total in x 100%.",) Tj
T* (                      "$= \\\\dfrac{350}{500} \\\\times 100\\\\%$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$= 70\\\\%$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "70% efficient. The other 150 J \(30%\) escaped as waste heat and sound -- the unavoidable ) Tj
T* (tax.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Where the bulb's energy goes",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "An old incandescent bulb is about 10% efficient at making light. If it draws 60 J of ) Tj
T* (electrical energy each second, how much becomes light, and what happens to the rest?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Useful light = 10% of 60 J.",) Tj
T* (                      "$0.10 \\\\times 60 = 6$ J of light per second.",) Tj
T* (                      "The remaining 54 J becomes heat.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
ET
endstream
