(              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Average acceleration** is the change in velocity per unit time:\\n\\n$$\\\\bar a = ) Tj
T* (\\\\frac{\\\\Delta v}{\\\\Delta t} = \\\\frac{v_f - v_i}{\\\\Delta t}$$\\n\\nUnits are metres per second per second, ) Tj
T* ($\\\\text{m/s}^2$.\\n\\nThe **instantaneous acceleration** is the derivative of velocity -- and therefore the second ) Tj
T* (derivative of position:\\n\\n$$a = \\\\frac{dv}{dt} = \\\\frac{d^2x}{dt^2}$$\\n\\n**Sign and direction.** Acceleration is a ) Tj
T* (vector. A common trap: *negative acceleration does not always mean \\"slowing down.\\"* What matters is the acceleration's) Tj
T* ( direction **relative to the velocity**:\\n\\n- If $a$ points the **same way** as $v$, the object speeds up.\\n- If $a$ ) Tj
T* (points **opposite** to $v$, the object slows down \(this is what we usually call *deceleration*\).\\n\\nSo a ball moving in ) Tj
T* (the $-x$ direction \($v<0$\) with $a<0$ is actually speeding up.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
