T* (          "slug": "kinematic-equations",) Tj
T* (          "title": "The Kinematic Equations",) Tj
T* (          "tagline": "Four equations that solve constant-acceleration motion",) Tj
T* (          "estMinutes": 18,) Tj
T* (          "xpReward": 160,) Tj
T* (          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "earth",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "The Equations of Motion",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "When acceleration is constant, four compact equations let you predict an object's entire future ) Tj
T* (-- position, velocity, and time.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why this matters",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Constant acceleration is everywhere: a dropped object, a braking car, a puck on ice given a) Tj
T* ( steady push. For these, you don't need calculus on every problem -- four **kinematic equations** package the answers. ) Tj
T* (Master choosing the right one and you can solve the vast majority of intro-mechanics problems.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The four equations",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "For motion with **constant acceleration** $a$, with initial velocity $v_0$, final velocity ) Tj
T* ($v$, and displacement $\\\\Delta x$ over time $t$:\\n\\n$$v = v_0 + at$$\\n$$\\\\Delta x = v_0 t + \\\\tfrac{1}{2}a t^2$$\\n$$v^2 ) Tj
T* (= v_0^2 + 2a\\\\,\\\\Delta x$$\\n$$\\\\Delta x = \\\\tfrac{1}{2}\(v_0 + v\)\\\\,t$$\\n\\n**How to choose.** Each equation is missing ) Tj
T* (exactly one of the five quantities $\\\\{v_0, v, a, t, \\\\Delta x\\\\}$. Identify what you know and what you want, then pick ) Tj
T* (the equation that doesn't involve the variable you neither know nor need:\\n\\n- No $\\\\Delta x$? Use $v = v_0 + at$.\\n- No) Tj
T* ( $v$? Use $\\\\Delta x = v_0 t + \\\\tfrac12 a t^2$.\\n- No $t$? Use $v^2 = v_0^2 + 2a\\\\,\\\\Delta x$.\\n- No $a$? Use $\\\\Delta ) Tj
T* (x = \\\\tfrac12\(v_0+v\)t$ \(displacement = average velocity x time\).\\n\\n**Where they come from \(calculus\).** Starting from ) Tj
