(              "title": "Why this matters",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "For two thousand years people believed motion needed a constant cause -- that a moving ) Tj
T* (object naturally slows and stops. Galileo and then Newton overturned this: objects slow down because of **friction**, ) Tj
T* (not because stopping is their natural state. Remove the friction and motion persists forever. This single idea launched ) Tj
T* (modern physics.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Newton's First Law:** An object at rest stays at rest, and an object in motion stays in ) Tj
T* (motion at **constant velocity** \(same speed, same straight-line direction\), **unless acted on by a net external ) Tj
T* (force.**\\n\\nThe tendency of an object to resist changes to its motion is called **inertia**, and the measure of inertia ) Tj
T* (is the object's **mass**. More mass => more inertia => harder to start, stop, or turn.\\n\\nThe crucial phrase is *net* ) Tj
T* (force. Forces are vectors; what matters is their sum:\\n\\n$$\\\\vec F_{net} = \\\\sum \\\\vec F$$\\n\\nWhen $\\\\vec F_{net} = 0$, ) Tj
T* (the object is in **equilibrium**: it stays at rest or keeps moving at constant velocity. A book on a table is in ) Tj
T* (equilibrium -- gravity pulls it down, the table's normal force pushes up with equal strength, and they cancel.\\n\\nSo ) Tj
T* (constant velocity \(including zero\) needs **no** net force. Only a *change* in velocity -- acceleration -- requires one.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "The book on the table",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A book sits motionless on a table. What is the net force on it?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "It isn't accelerating \(it's at rest\), so by the first law the net force must be zero.",) Tj
T* (                      "Gravity \(down\) is exactly balanced by the table's normal force \(up\).") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Zero net force -- the forces are balanced \(equilibrium\).") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Seatbelt physics",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A car brakes suddenly and the passengers lurch forward. Why?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Before braking, passengers move forward at the car's speed.",) Tj
T* (                      "By inertia, they tend to keep moving forward when the car decelerates.",) Tj
T* (                      "The seatbelt supplies the backward force needed to change their motion.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Inertia keeps the passengers moving; the seatbelt provides the force to stop them.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Puck on ice",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A hockey puck glides across nearly frictionless ice. What keeps it moving?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Nothing needs to keep it moving -- that's the first law.",) Tj
T* (                      "With negligible friction and no net force, it continues at constant velocity.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "No force is needed; it coasts at constant velocity until friction or a wall acts.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
T* (                ]) Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
