T* (                "headline": "Resisting Motion",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "Friction is why you can walk and why nothing slides forever -- a force born where surfaces ) Tj
T* (meet.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why this matters",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Friction is the hidden force in nearly every mechanics problem. It lets tyres grip, brakes ) Tj
T* (work, and knots hold -- yet it also wastes energy as heat and wears parts down. Knowing when it helps, when it hurts, ) Tj
T* (and how to compute it is essential.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Friction** is a force that opposes \(or tends to oppose\) relative sliding between two ) Tj
T* (surfaces in contact. It always acts **parallel to the surface**, opposite to the motion or attempted motion.\\n\\nFriction) Tj
T* ( comes in two flavours:\\n\\n- **Static friction** acts when surfaces are *not yet* sliding. It adjusts itself to match ) Tj
T* (whatever you apply, up to a maximum:\\n\\n$$f_s \\\\le \\\\mu_s N$$\\n\\n- **Kinetic friction** acts when surfaces *are* ) Tj
T* (sliding, with a roughly constant value:\\n\\n$$f_k = \\\\mu_k N$$\\n\\nHere $N$ is the **normal force** \(the perpendicular ) Tj
T* (push between the surfaces\) and $\\\\mu$ \(mu\) is the dimensionless **coefficient of friction** -- a property of the two ) Tj
T* (materials. Usually $\\\\mu_s > \\\\mu_k$, which is why it takes a bigger push to *start* something sliding than to keep it ) Tj
T* (sliding.\\n\\nKey facts: friction is proportional to the **normal force**, not to the contact area or speed \(to a good ) Tj
T* (approximation\), and it converts mechanical energy into **heat**.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SIMULATION",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Try it: ramp & friction",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "simId": "incline-plane",) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Raise the angle and change mu. Watch the normal force, the friction force, and whether the ) Tj
T* (block slides -- it gives way exactly when $\\\\tan\\\\theta > \\\\mu$.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
