T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "sun",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Forces on a Ramp",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "A ramp is the ultimate test of dynamics: gravity, the normal force, and friction all at once -- ) Tj
T* (solved by choosing clever axes.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why this matters",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Ramps, hills, slides, wheelchair access, and mountain roads are all inclined planes. The ) Tj
T* (technique you learn here -- tilting your coordinate axes and splitting gravity into components -- is the single most ) Tj
T* (important problem-solving skill in introductory mechanics.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "On an incline tilted at angle $\\\\theta$, gravity still points straight down -- but it's ) Tj
T* (convenient to **tilt the axes** so one points *along* the ramp and the other *perpendicular* to it. Then split the ) Tj
T* (weight $mg$ into two components:\\n\\n- **Along the ramp \(down-slope\):** $\\\\;mg\\\\sin\\\\theta$ -- this is what tends to ) Tj
T* (accelerate the object down.\\n- **Perpendicular to the ramp:** $\\\\;mg\\\\cos\\\\theta$ -- this is balanced by the **normal ) Tj
T* (force**, so\\n\\n$$N = mg\\\\cos\\\\theta.$$\\n\\n**Frictionless incline.** The only unbalanced force is $mg\\\\sin\\\\theta$ ) Tj
T* (down-slope, so by $F=ma$:\\n\\n$$a = g\\\\sin\\\\theta.$$\\n\\nNotice the mass cancels -- every object slides down a ) Tj
T* (frictionless ramp with the same acceleration, just as in free fall \(the $\\\\theta = 90^\\\\circ$ case gives $a = ) Tj
T* (g$\).\\n\\n**With friction.** Kinetic friction $f_k = \\\\mu N = \\\\mu mg\\\\cos\\\\theta$ acts up-slope. The net down-slope force) Tj
T* ( is $mg\\\\sin\\\\theta - \\\\mu mg\\\\cos\\\\theta$, giving\\n\\n$$a = g\(\\\\sin\\\\theta - \\\\mu\\\\cos\\\\theta\).$$\\n\\nThe block only ) Tj
T* (begins to slide when the down-slope pull exceeds maximum static friction -- that is, when $\\\\tan\\\\theta > \\\\mu$.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SIMULATION",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Try it: the ramp",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "simId": "incline-plane",) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Dial in the angle and friction, watch the force components and the normal force, then release ) Tj
T* (the block to see $a = g\(\\\\sin\\\\theta - \\\\mu\\\\cos\\\\theta\)$ play out.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Frictionless ramp",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A block slides down a frictionless ramp inclined at $30^\\\\circ$. Find its acceleration ) Tj
T* (\($g = 9.8\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}^2$\).",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "With no friction, $a = g\\\\sin\\\\theta$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$a = 9.8 \\\\times \\\\sin 30^\\\\circ = 9.8 \\\\times 0.5 = 4.9\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}^2$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$a = 4.9\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}^2$ down the ramp \(independent of mass\).") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Normal force",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A $4.0\\\\,\\\\text{kg}$ block rests on a $30^\\\\circ$ incline. Find the normal force \($g = ) Tj
T* (9.8$\).",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$N = mg\\\\cos\\\\theta = 4.0 \\\\times 9.8 \\\\times \\\\cos 30^\\\\circ$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$= 39.2 \\\\times 0.866 \\\\approx 33.9\\\\,\\\\text{N}$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$N \\\\approx 33.9\\\\,\\\\text{N}$ \(less than the full weight of $39.2\\\\,\\\\text{N}$\).") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
ET
endstream
