T* (                "markdown": "The formula $W = Fd\\\\cos\\\\theta$ is really the **dot product** of two vectors, $W = \\\\vec F) Tj
T* ( \\\\cdot \\\\vec d$. The cosine is what the dot product extracts: the part of the force that lies along the ) Tj
T* (displacement.\\n\\nWhen the force **varies** along the path, we slice the path into tiny pieces and add up the work on ) Tj
T* (each, which in the limit becomes an integral:\\n\\n$$W = \\\\int \\\\vec F \\\\cdot d\\\\vec r.$$\\n\\nThis is how you compute the ) Tj
T* (work done by a stretching spring, whose force grows with distance -- a calculation you'll meet again in the next ) Tj
T* (lessons.") Tj
