T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Why does a car need four times the braking distance when it doubles its speed? Kinetic ) Tj
T* (energy holds the answer: it grows with the **square** of speed. The work-energy theorem turns messy ) Tj
T* (force-and-acceleration problems into clean energy bookkeeping.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Kinetic energy** is the energy an object has because of its motion:\\n\\n$$K = \\\\tfrac12 m ) Tj
T* (v^2$$\\n\\nIt depends on mass and on the **square** of speed -- double the speed and the kinetic energy **quadruples**. ) Tj
T* (Like all energy, it's measured in **joules** and is always $\\\\ge 0$.\\n\\nThe **work-energy theorem** ties work and ) Tj
T* (kinetic energy together: the **net work** done on an object equals its **change in kinetic energy**:\\n\\n$$W_{net} = ) Tj
T* (\\\\Delta K = \\\\tfrac12 m v_f^2 - \\\\tfrac12 m v_i^2$$\\n\\nThis is one of the most useful results in mechanics. If you know ) Tj
T* (the net work, you instantly know how the speed changes -- no need to track acceleration and time. Positive net work ) Tj
T* (speeds an object up; negative net work \(like friction or braking\) slows it down.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
