(        },) Tj
T* (        {) Tj
T* (          "slug": "conservation-of-energy",) Tj
T* (          "title": "Conservation of Energy",) Tj
T* (          "tagline": "Energy changes form but is never lost",) Tj
T* (          "estMinutes": 16,) Tj
T* (          "xpReward": 190,) Tj
T* (          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "sun",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Energy Is Conserved",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "In the absence of friction, kinetic and potential energy trade back and forth -- but their sum ) Tj
T* (stays exactly the same.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why this matters",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Conservation of energy is one of the deepest laws in all of science. A roller coaster, a ) Tj
T* (swinging pendulum, a falling apple -- all obey it. It lets you find a final speed from a starting height in a single ) Tj
T* (line, sidestepping forces and time entirely.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Define the **total mechanical energy** as kinetic plus potential:\\n\\n$$E = K + ) Tj
T* (U.$$\\n\\n**Conservation of mechanical energy:** when only gravity and springs act \(no friction or air resistance\), the ) Tj
T* (total mechanical energy stays **constant**:\\n\\n$$K_i + U_i = K_f + U_f.$$\\n\\nEnergy is not created or destroyed -- it ) Tj
T* (merely **converts** between forms. As a ball falls, $U_g = mgh$ shrinks while $K = \\\\tfrac12 mv^2$ grows by exactly the ) Tj
T* (same amount, keeping the sum fixed.\\n\\nA classic result: drop an object from height $h$ \(from rest\). All its potential ) Tj
T* (energy becomes kinetic energy at the bottom:\\n\\n$$mgh = \\\\tfrac12 m v^2 \\\\;\\\\Rightarrow\\\\; v = \\\\sqrt{2gh}.$$\\n\\nThe ) Tj
T* (mass cancels -- every object reaches the same speed from the same height \(without friction\).\\n\\n**With friction**, ) Tj
T* (mechanical energy is *not* conserved on its own: friction converts some into **heat**. But counting heat too, the ) Tj
T* (*total* energy of everything is still conserved -- that's the universal law.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SIMULATION",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Try it: the energy ledger",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "simId": "energy-bars",) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Drop the ball from any height. Watch PE and KE trade places while the green Total bar never ) Tj
T* (moves -- that's conservation of energy in action.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Speed at the bottom",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A ball is dropped from rest at $5.0\\\\,\\\\text{m}$. Find its speed just before it lands ) Tj
T* (\($g = 9.8$, no air resistance\).",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "All PE becomes KE: $mgh = \\\\tfrac12 mv^2$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$v = \\\\sqrt{2gh} = \\\\sqrt{2 \\\\times 9.8 \\\\times 5.0} = \\\\sqrt{98}$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$v \\\\approx 9.9\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$v \\\\approx 9.9\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}$ \(mass-independent\).") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Pendulum swing",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A pendulum is released from a height $0.20\\\\,\\\\text{m}$ above its lowest point. How fast) Tj
T* ( is it moving at the bottom? \($g = 9.8$.\)",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$v = \\\\sqrt{2gh} = \\\\sqrt{2 \\\\times 9.8 \\\\times 0.20}$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$= \\\\sqrt{3.92} \\\\approx 2.0\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$v \\\\approx 2.0\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Where friction goes",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A sled slides to a stop on level ground. Where did its kinetic energy go?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "No height change, so gravitational PE is unchanged.",) Tj
T* (                      "Friction did negative work on the sled.",) Tj
ET
