T* (          "slug": "moment-of-inertia",) Tj
T* (          "title": "Moment of Inertia & Rotational Newton's Law",) Tj
T* (          "tagline": "Rotational mass and tau = Ialpha",) Tj
T* (          "estMinutes": 15,) Tj
T* (          "xpReward": 180,) Tj
T* (          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "sun",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Resistance to Spinning",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "Mass resists acceleration; moment of inertia resists angular acceleration -- and depends on how ) Tj
T* (that mass is spread out.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why this matters",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Why does a figure skater spin faster when they pull their arms in? Why is a solid disk ) Tj
T* (easier to spin than a ring of the same mass? The answer is **moment of inertia** -- rotational mass -- which depends not) Tj
T* ( just on how much mass there is, but on *where* it sits relative to the axis.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Moment of inertia** $I$ is the rotational equivalent of mass -- an object's resistance to) Tj
T* ( angular acceleration. For a single point mass at distance $r$ from the axis:\\n\\n$$I = m r^2.$$\\n\\nFor an extended body,) Tj
T* ( you add up $mr^2$ over all its parts. The key insight: mass **farther from the axis** counts much more \(it's squared\). ) Tj
T* (So a hoop \(all mass at the rim\) has a larger $I$ than a solid disk of the same mass and radius. Standard results:\\n\\n- ) Tj
T* (solid disk/cylinder: $I = \\\\tfrac12 MR^2$\\n- thin hoop/ring: $I = MR^2$\\n- solid sphere: $I = \\\\tfrac25 ) Tj
T* (MR^2$\\n\\n**Newton's second law for rotation.** Torque plays the role of force, $I$ the role of mass, and $\\\\alpha$ the ) Tj
T* (role of acceleration:\\n\\n$$\\\\tau_{net} = I\\\\,\\\\alpha.$$\\n\\nGive the same torque to a larger $I$ and it spins up more ) Tj
T* (slowly -- exactly as a larger mass accelerates more slowly under the same force.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Point mass",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Find the moment of inertia of a $2.0\\\\,\\\\text{kg}$ mass at the end of a ) Tj
T* ($3.0\\\\,\\\\text{m}$ massless rod \(axis at the other end\).",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$I = mr^2 = 2.0 \\\\times \(3.0\)^2$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$= 2.0 \\\\times 9.0 = 18\\\\,\\\\text{kg*m}^2$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$I = 18\\\\,\\\\text{kg*m}^2$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
ET
