T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A rotating object has **rotational kinetic energy**, the spin analogue of $\\\\tfrac12 ) Tj
T* (mv^2$:\\n\\n$$K_{rot} = \\\\tfrac12 I \\\\omega^2.$$\\n\\nA **rolling** object \(like a wheel or ball\) has *both* kinds at once ) Tj
T* (-- its center moves *and* it spins:\\n\\n$$K_{total} = \\\\tfrac12 m v^2 + \\\\tfrac12 I \\\\omega^2.$$\\n\\nFor rolling **without) Tj
T* ( slipping**, the two are linked by $v = r\\\\omega$.\\n\\nThis explains the famous downhill race. When objects roll down a ) Tj
T* (ramp, gravitational PE splits between translation and rotation. An object with a **larger** moment of inertia \(for its ) Tj
T* (mass and radius\) puts more energy into spin and less into forward speed -- so it rolls **slower**. The ranking from ) Tj
T* (fastest to slowest:\\n\\n$$\\\\text{sphere} \\\\;>\\\\; \\\\text{disk} \\\\;>\\\\; \\\\text{hoop}.$$\\n\\nA hoop \(all mass at the rim, ) Tj
T* (largest $I$\) always loses; a solid sphere always wins. Remarkably, the result is **independent of mass and radius** -- ) Tj
T* (only the *shape* \(the $I$-to-$mr^2$ ratio\) matters.") Tj
