T* (                "headline": "Always Falling Inward",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "An object moving in a circle at steady speed is still accelerating -- because its direction ) Tj
T* (never stops changing.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why a planet doesn't fly off",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Earth races around the Sun at about $30\\\\,\\\\text{km/s}$, yet it neither speeds up nor flies) Tj
T* ( away. Its **speed** is constant but its **velocity** is not -- velocity is a vector, and its direction turns ) Tj
T* (continuously. A changing velocity means acceleration, and acceleration needs a force. Understanding that force is the ) Tj
T* (key to every orbit.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "In **uniform circular motion** an object moves in a circle of radius $r$ at constant speed ) Tj
T* ($v$. The velocity is always **tangent** to the circle, so its direction changes constantly -- that is an acceleration ) Tj
T* (even though the speed is fixed.\\n\\nThis **centripetal** \('center-seeking'\) acceleration points toward the ) Tj
T* (center:\\n\\n$$a_c = \\\\frac{v^2}{r}.$$\\n\\nBy Newton's second law it requires a net inward **centripetal force**:\\n\\n$$F_c ) Tj
T* (= m a_c = \\\\frac{m v^2}{r}.$$\\n\\nThe time for one full loop is the **period** $T$, and since the object covers a ) Tj
T* (circumference $2\\\\pi r$ in that time,\\n\\n$$v = \\\\frac{2\\\\pi r}{T}.$$\\n\\nThe centripetal force is not a new kind of force) Tj
T* ( -- it is whatever real force \(gravity, tension, friction\) happens to point toward the center.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Centripetal acceleration",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A car rounds a circle of radius $20\\\\,\\\\text{m}$ at $10\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}$. Find $a_c$.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Use $a_c = v^2/r$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$a_c = 10^2 / 20 = 100/20$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$a_c = 5\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}^2$ toward the center.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Centripetal force",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A $2\\\\,\\\\text{kg}$ mass in that same turn needs what inward force?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$F_c = m a_c$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$F_c = 2 \\\\times 5$.") Tj
ET
