/F1 7.2 Tf
8.6 TL
40 744.8 Td
(              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "The light reaching us from a binary star crossed light-years of space as a **wave**. So ) Tj
T* (does the sound of a voice, the ripple on a pond, and the signal in a fibre. A wave is a self-propagating oscillation -- ) Tj
T* (and one simple equation links its speed, frequency, and wavelength.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A **wave** is a disturbance that carries energy through a medium \(or, for light, through ) Tj
T* (space\) while the medium itself only oscillates locally.\\n\\nKey quantities:\\n\\n- **Wavelength** $\\\\lambda$: distance ) Tj
T* (between successive crests.\\n- **Frequency** $f$: oscillations per second \(Hz\).\\n- **Amplitude**: the oscillation's size ) Tj
T* (\(loudness for sound, brightness for light\).\\n- **Speed** $v$: how fast a crest travels.\\n\\nThe master relation:\\n\\n$$v =) Tj
T* ( f\\\\lambda.$$\\n\\nFor a fixed speed, higher frequency means shorter wavelength. **Transverse** waves oscillate ) Tj
T* (perpendicular to travel \(light, a plucked string\); **longitudinal** waves oscillate along the travel direction \(sound, ) Tj
T* (as compressions of air\). Sound travels at about $340\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}$ in air; light at $3\\\\times10^8\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}$.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Wave speed",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "A wave has $f = 5\\\\,\\\\text{Hz}$ and $\\\\lambda = 2\\\\,\\\\text{m}$. Find its speed.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$v = f\\\\lambda$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$5 \\\\times 2 = 10$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$v = 10\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Find wavelength",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Sound at $340\\\\,\\\\text{m/s}$ and $f = 170\\\\,\\\\text{Hz}$. Find $\\\\lambda$.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$\\\\lambda = v/f$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$340/170 = 2$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$\\\\lambda = 2\\\\,\\\\text{m}$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Type of wave",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Is sound transverse or longitudinal?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Air compresses along the travel direction.",) Tj
T* (                      "Oscillation is parallel to motion.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Longitudinal.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
T* (                ]) Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT_CHECK",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Quick check",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "$v = f\\\\lambda$ ties speed, frequency, wavelength.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "PRACTICE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Practice problems",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Rearrange $v = f\\\\lambda$ as needed.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "DEEPER_DIVE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Deeper dive: the Doppler effect",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "When a wave source moves toward you, the crests bunch up -- shorter wavelength, higher ) Tj
T* (frequency; moving away, they stretch -- lower frequency. That's the **Doppler effect**: the rising-then-falling pitch of) Tj
T* ( a passing siren, and, for light, the **redshift** of receding galaxies. Astronomers measure the Doppler wobble of a ) Tj
T* (star to detect unseen companions -- exactly how many binary systems and exoplanets are found.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SUMMARY",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Summary",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
ET
