T* (                "scene": "sun",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Color Is Temperature",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "A star's color, brightness, and size are locked together by the physics of glowing objects.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Decoding starlight",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "We can't visit a star, yet we know its temperature, size, and power output -- all from its ) Tj
T* (light. The key is **blackbody radiation**: any hot object glows with a spectrum set purely by its temperature, and stars) Tj
T* ( are nearly perfect blackbodies.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A hot object emits **blackbody radiation** governed by two laws:\\n\\n- **Wien's law:** ) Tj
T* (hotter means bluer. The peak wavelength satisfies $\\\\lambda_{\\\\text{peak}} \\\\propto \\\\dfrac{1}{T}$. So red stars are ) Tj
T* (cool, blue stars are hot.\\n- **Stefan-Boltzmann law:** the power radiated per unit area grows as the fourth power of ) Tj
T* (temperature, $\\\\propto T^4$. For a whole star of radius $R$,\\n\\n$$L = 4\\\\pi R^2 \\\\sigma T^4.$$\\n\\n**Luminosity** $L$ is ) Tj
T* (the star's total power output. Because of the $T^4$, a small rise in temperature hugely boosts luminosity; because of ) Tj
T* ($R^2$, a bigger star is far brighter at the same temperature.\\n\\n**Apparent brightness** \(how bright it *looks*\) also ) Tj
T* (falls off with distance by the inverse-square law, so a star's distance must be known to turn its apparent brightness ) Tj
T* (into true luminosity.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Color and temperature",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Which is hotter, a red star or a blue star?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Wien: hotter peaks bluer.",) Tj
T* (                      "Blue -> higher T.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "The blue star.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Temperature scaling",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "If a star's temperature doubles \(same size\), how does luminosity change?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$L \\\\propto T^4$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$2^4 = 16$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "16 times brighter.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Size scaling",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Two stars at the same T; one has twice the radius. Luminosity ratio?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$L \\\\propto R^2$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$2^2 = 4$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "4 times brighter.") Tj
ET
endstream
