(                "markdown": "The **Hertzsprung-Russell \(HR\) diagram** plots **luminosity** \(true brightness\) on the ) Tj
T* (vertical axis against **surface temperature** on the horizontal \(running hot-to-cool, left-to-right\). Stars are not ) Tj
T* (scattered randomly -- they cluster into groups:\\n\\n- **The main sequence** -- a diagonal band from hot-bright \(top-left\)) Tj
T* ( to cool-dim \(bottom-right\) where stars spend most of their lives fusing hydrogen. The Sun sits here, mid-band. A star's) Tj
T* ( **position on the main sequence is set by its mass**: massive stars are hot, bright, blue, and short-lived; small stars) Tj
T* ( are cool, dim, red, and long-lived.\\n- **Red giants** -- cool but luminous \(top-right\): huge, swollen, late-life ) Tj
T* (stars.\\n- **White dwarfs** -- hot but faint \(bottom-left\): tiny, dense stellar corpses.\\n\\nA star **traces a path** ) Tj
T* (across the diagram as it ages: born onto the main sequence, swelling into a red giant when its core hydrogen runs low, ) Tj
T* (then ending as a white dwarf \(or, if massive, exploding\). Reading a star's spot on the HR diagram tells you what it is ) Tj
T* (and where it is in its life.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
