T* (                "headline": "Surveying the Universe",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "No tape measure reaches a star -- so astronomers built a ladder of clever methods, each ) Tj
T* (calibrating the next.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "How far is far?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Knowing a star's brightness or a galaxy's speed is useless without its **distance**. But ) Tj
T* (distances in space are unimaginable. Astronomers solved it with a **distance ladder**: a sequence of techniques, each ) Tj
T* (reaching farther and calibrated by the rung below.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Three key rungs:\\n\\n**1. Parallax \(nearby stars\).** As Earth orbits the Sun, nearby stars ) Tj
T* (appear to shift slightly against distant ones -- like a finger held up and viewed with each eye in turn. The bigger the ) Tj
T* (shift, the closer the star. This is direct geometry, the ladder's foundation.\\n\\n**2. Standard candles \(distant stars ) Tj
T* (and galaxies\).** Some objects have a known true **luminosity** $L$. Compare it to how bright they *appear*, $b$, and the) Tj
T* ( distance follows from the **inverse-square law**:\\n\\n$$b = \\\\frac{L}{4\\\\pi d^2}.$$\\n\\nBrightness falls off as $1/d^2$, ) Tj
T* (so a known $L$ plus a measured $b$ gives $d$. **Cepheid variable** stars \(whose pulse period reveals their luminosity\) ) Tj
T* (and **Type Ia supernovae** \(which all explode with nearly the same luminosity\) are the great standard candles, reaching ) Tj
T* (across billions of light-years.\\n\\n**3. Redshift \(the farthest galaxies\).** The expansion of the universe stretches ) Tj
T* (light from distant galaxies toward longer \(redder\) wavelengths. Via **Hubble's law**, redshift gives recession speed and) Tj
T* ( hence distance for the most remote objects.\\n\\nEach rung calibrates the next: parallax pins down nearby Cepheids, ) Tj
T* (Cepheids calibrate supernovae, supernovae anchor the redshift scale. The whole ladder lets us map the universe out to ) Tj
T* (its edge.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Why parallax shows distance",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Why do nearer stars shift more over a year?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Parallax is the apparent shift from Earth's orbit.",) Tj
T* (                      "Closer objects shift more.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "A larger parallax means a nearer star.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Brightness and distance",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "If a standard candle is moved twice as far, how bright does it look?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Brightness $\\\\propto 1/d^2$.",) Tj
T* (                      "Double $d$ gives $1/4$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "One quarter as bright.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Reaching the farthest",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "How are the most distant galaxies' distances found?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Their light is redshifted by expansion.",) Tj
T* (                      "Hubble's law converts redshift to distance.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "By redshift and Hubble's law.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
T* (                ]) Tj
ET
endstream
