T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The hottest gas in the universe",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "The space between galaxies in a cluster is filled with gas at tens of millions of degrees, ) Tj
T* (glowing in X-rays. To understand such a system -- or a steam engine, or a star -- we need **thermodynamics**: the ) Tj
T* (physics of temperature, heat, and the statistical behavior of countless particles.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Temperature** measures the average **kinetic energy** of a substance's particles. ) Tj
T* (**Heat** $Q$ is energy transferred *because of* a temperature difference, and it always flows from hot to cold.\\n\\nThe ) Tj
T* (**absolute \(Kelvin\)** scale starts at **absolute zero** \($0\\\\,\\\\text{K} = -273^\\\\circ\\\\text{C}$\), where particle motion ) Tj
T* (is minimal.\\n\\nFor an **ideal gas**, pressure $P$, volume $V$, and temperature $T$ obey the **ideal gas law**:\\n\\n$$PV =) Tj
T* ( nRT,$$\\n\\nwhere $n$ is the amount of gas and $R$ the gas constant. Consequences at fixed amount:\\n\\n- At constant $T$: ) Tj
T* ($P$ and $V$ trade off \($PV$ constant\) -- squeeze a gas and pressure rises.\\n- At constant $V$: heating raises pressure ) Tj
T* (\($P \\\\propto T$\).\\n\\n**Kinetic theory** explains why: pressure is just countless molecules drumming on the walls, and ) Tj
T* (raising $T$ makes them hit harder and more often.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
