(                "markdown": "Heat engines drove the Industrial Revolution and still generate most of our electricity. ) Tj
T* (The second law sets an unbreakable limit on them -- discovered by a young engineer studying steam, and as fundamental as) Tj
T* ( any law in physics.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A **heat engine** takes in heat from a hot reservoir at temperature $T_h$, converts ) Tj
T* (**some** of it into useful work, and dumps the rest into a cold reservoir at $T_c$. It *must* dump some -- the second ) Tj
T* (law forbids turning heat entirely into work.\\n\\nThe **maximum possible efficiency**, achieved only by an ideal ) Tj
T* (\(reversible\) **Carnot** engine, depends only on the two temperatures \(in kelvin\):\\n\\n$$\\\\eta_{max} = 1 - ) Tj
T* (\\\\frac{T_c}{T_h}.$$\\n\\nLessons from this formula:\\n\\n- A bigger temperature gap \(hotter $T_h$ or colder $T_c$\) means ) Tj
T* (higher possible efficiency.\\n- Perfect efficiency \($\\\\eta = 1$\) would need $T_c = 0$ \(absolute zero\) -- impossible by ) Tj
T* (the third law.\\n- Real engines, with friction and irreversibility, always fall **below** the Carnot limit.\\n\\nThis is ) Tj
T* (why power plants run boilers as hot as materials allow, and why no 'perfect' engine can exist. Run an engine in reverse ) Tj
T* (and you get a **refrigerator** or **heat pump**, using work to move heat from cold to hot -- paying the entropy bill ) Tj
T* (with the work input.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Carnot efficiency",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "An ideal engine runs between $T_h = 600$ K and $T_c = 300$ K. What is its maximum ) Tj
T* (efficiency?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Use $\\\\eta_{max} = 1 - T_c/T_h$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$= 1 - 300/600$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$= 1 - 0.5 = 0.5$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "50% -- and a real engine between these temperatures does worse.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Why dump heat?",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Why can't an engine turn all its input heat into work?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "The second law forbids it.",) Tj
T* (                      "Some heat must go to the cold reservoir.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Exhaust heat is unavoidable.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Boosting efficiency",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "How do you raise an engine's efficiency ceiling?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Increase the temperature gap.",) Tj
T* (                      "Raise $T_h$ or lower $T_c$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Widen the gap between hot and cold.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
T* (                ]) Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT_CHECK",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Quick check",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "$\\\\eta_{max} = 1 - T_c/T_h$; perfect efficiency is impossible.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "PRACTICE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Practice problems",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Compute and reason about engine efficiency.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "DEEPER_DIVE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Deeper dive: Carnot's lasting legacy",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Sadi Carnot** published his analysis in 1824 and died of cholera at 36, his work nearly ) Tj
T* (forgotten. Yet his idealized engine set the gold standard every real engine is measured against, and his reasoning ) Tj
T* (birthed the second law and the concept of entropy. Remarkably, the Carnot limit depends *only* on temperatures -- not on) Tj
T* ( the working substance, design, or fuel. It's a statement about the universe, not about engineering, which is why it has) Tj
T* ( never been beaten.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
ET
endstream
endobj
