stream
BT
/F1 7.2 Tf
8.6 TL
40 744.8 Td
(              "title": "Timing the universe",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Having met the nucleus and radioactivity, we now quantify it. The **half-life** turns ) Tj
T* (random nuclear decay into one of science's most powerful tools, dating everything from prehistoric campfires to the age ) Tj
T* (of the Earth and the cosmos.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A radioactive nucleus is unstable and will eventually **decay**, emitting radiation. You ) Tj
T* (can't predict *when* a single nucleus decays -- it's random -- but a huge collection decays at a precise statistical ) Tj
T* (rate.\\n\\nThe **half-life** $t_{1/2}$ is the time for **half** of the nuclei in a sample to decay. After each half-life, ) Tj
T* (half of what remains is left:\\n\\n$$N = N_0 \\\\left\(\\\\tfrac{1}{2}\\\\right\)^{n}, \\\\qquad n = \\\\frac{t}{t_{1/2}}.$$\\n\\nSo ) Tj
T* (after 1 half-life, $1/2$ remains; after 2, $1/4$; after 3, $1/8$; and so on. Half-lives range from fractions of a second) Tj
T* ( to billions of years.\\n\\nThree decay types differ in penetrating power:\\n\\n- **Alpha** \($\\\\alpha$\): a helium nucleus; ) Tj
T* (heavy, stopped by paper.\\n- **Beta** \($\\\\beta$\): a fast electron; stopped by aluminum.\\n- **Gamma** \($\\\\gamma$\): ) Tj
T* (high-energy photon; needs thick lead or concrete.\\n\\n**Radiometric dating** uses this clock. **Carbon-14** \(half-life ) Tj
T* (~5,700 years\) dates organic remains up to ~50,000 years; **uranium** isotopes \(billions of years\) date rocks and ) Tj
T* (meteorites -- that's how we know the Earth is about 4.5 billion years old.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Three half-lives",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "An 80 g sample has a half-life of 5 years. How much remains after 15 years?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$n = 15/5 = 3$ half-lives.",) Tj
T* (                      "Halve three times: $80 \\\\to 40 \\\\to 20 \\\\to 10$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "10 g remain.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Reading the fraction",) Tj
