T* (        {) Tj
T* (          "slug": "place-value-tens-and-ones",) Tj
T* (          "title": "Place Value -- Tens and Ones",) Tj
T* (          "tagline": "Why the spot a digit sits in matters",) Tj
T* (          "estMinutes": 13,) Tj
T* (          "xpReward": 120,) Tj
T* (          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "school",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Tens and Ones",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "The number 34 isn't a 3 and a 4 -- it's 3 tens and 4 ones. The place a digit sits in decides its) Tj
T* ( value.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Counting the whole class",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "There are too many pencils to count one by one, so the teacher bundles them into **groups ) Tj
T* (of ten** with a rubber band, then counts the loose ones left over. Four bundles and seven singles: **47 ) Tj
T* (pencils**.\\n\\nThis bundling is the secret behind every number we write. Our number system is built on **tens**, and the ) Tj
T* (*position* of each digit tells you how many ones, tens, hundreds, and so on it stands for. This idea -- **place value** ) Tj
T* (-- is what lets ten little symbols \(0-9\) write any number at all.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "In a two-digit number, there are two **places**, and each has a value ten times the one to ) Tj
T* (its right:\\n\\n- the **ones place** \(right\) -- worth 1 each\\n- the **tens place** \(left\) -- worth 10 each\\n\\nTake the ) Tj
T* (number **34**:\\n\\n$$34 = \\\\underbrace{3}_{\\\\text{tens}}\\\\,\\\\underbrace{4}_{\\\\text{ones}} = 3 \\\\times 10 + 4 \\\\times 1 = ) Tj
T* (30 + 4.$$\\n\\nThe **3** is not just \\"three\\" -- because it sits in the tens place, it is worth **30**. The **4** in the ) Tj
T* (ones place is worth **4**. Writing a number as $30 + 4$ is called **expanded form**.\\n\\nSo the same digit means ) Tj
T* (different amounts depending on *where* it sits. In **34** the 3 means 30; in **43** the 3 means just 3. Place is ) Tj
T* (everything.\\n\\nThe big rule that ties it together: **ten ones make one ten.** Whenever you gather ten loose ones, you ) Tj
T* (bundle them into a single ten and move one place to the left -- exactly what the rubber band did to the pencils.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
