T* (              "kind": "DEEPER_DIVE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Deeper dive: why base ten?",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Our whole system is called **base ten** because we bundle in groups of ten -- most likely ) Tj
T* (because humans have ten fingers. Each place to the left is worth ten times more: ones, tens, **hundreds** \($10\\\\times ) Tj
T* (10$\), **thousands** \($10\\\\times 100$\), and on forever.\\n\\nIt didn't have to be ten. Computers use **base two** \(binary\),) Tj
T* ( bundling in groups of two with only the digits 0 and 1. The Babylonians used base sixty -- which is why an hour still ) Tj
T* (has 60 minutes! But the *idea* is always the same: the position of a digit decides its value.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SUMMARY",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Summary",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "takeaways": [) Tj
T* (                  "A digit's value depends on its place.",) Tj
T* (                  "Two-digit numbers have a tens place and a ones place.",) Tj
T* (                  "$34 = 3 \\\\text{ tens} + 4 \\\\text{ ones} = 30 + 4$ \(expanded form\).",) Tj
T* (                  "Ten ones bundle into one ten -- the heart of base ten.",) Tj
T* (                  "The same digit means different amounts in different places.") Tj
T* (                ],) Tj
T* (                "formulas": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "label": "Place value",) Tj
T* (                    "tex": "\\\\overline{ab} = a \\\\times 10 + b") Tj
