(like addition, we subtract two-digit numbers **column by column** using place value -- but now the tricky part is what ) Tj
T* (to do when the top ones digit is too small to subtract from.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Line the numbers up by place and subtract each column, starting from the **ones** on the ) Tj
T* (right.\\n\\n**When the top digit is big enough** \(no borrowing\):\\n\\n$$47 - 23: \\\\quad 7 - 3 = 4 \\\\ \(\\\\text{ones}\), \\\\quad ) Tj
T* (4 - 2 = 2 \\\\ \(\\\\text{tens}\) \\\\;\\\\Rightarrow\\\\; 24.$$\\n\\n**When the top ones digit is too small**, you must **regroup** ) Tj
T* (\(also called **borrowing**\). Take one ten from the tens column and turn it into ten ones:\\n\\n$$42 - 17: \\\\quad ) Tj
T* (\\\\text{ones } 2 - 7 \\\\text{ won't work.}$$\\n\\nBorrow 1 ten from the 4 tens \(leaving 3 tens\) and add it to the 2 ones, ) Tj
T* (making **12 ones**:\\n\\n$$12 - 7 = 5 \\\\ \(\\\\text{ones}\), \\\\quad 3 - 1 = 2 \\\\ \(\\\\text{tens}\) \\\\;\\\\Rightarrow\\\\; ) Tj
T* (25.$$\\n\\nThe rule in one line: **subtract each column right to left; if the top digit is smaller than the bottom, borrow) Tj
T* ( a ten from the next column.** Borrowing is \\"one ten = ten ones\\" run in reverse of carrying.\\n\\n**Always check by ) Tj
T* (adding back:** if $42 - 17 = 25$, then $25 + 17$ should give $42$. It does -- so the answer is right.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
