(a few are left in the tin. To describe \\"how much\\" each person has, whole numbers aren't enough -- we need ) Tj
T* (**fractions**.\\n\\nFractions are everywhere: half a cup of flour, a quarter past three, three-quarters of a tank of gas. ) Tj
T* (Master them at the bakery and you've unlocked the rest of arithmetic.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A **fraction** names a part of a whole that has been split into **equal** parts. It's ) Tj
T* (written with two numbers:\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{3}{4} \\\\quad\\\\leftarrow\\\\; \\\\text{numerator \(parts you have\)} \\\\atop ) Tj
T* (\\\\leftarrow\\\\; \\\\text{denominator \(equal parts in the whole\)}$$\\n\\n- The **denominator** \(bottom\) tells how many ) Tj
T* (**equal** parts the whole is cut into.\\n- The **numerator** \(top\) tells how many of those parts you're talking ) Tj
T* (about.\\n\\nSo $\\\\tfrac{3}{4}$ means: cut the pie into **4** equal slices, and take **3** of them.\\n\\nKey ideas:\\n\\n- The ) Tj
T* (parts must be **equal**. Three random chunks of a pie are not \\"three-quarters\\" unless the pie was cut into four equal ) Tj
T* (pieces.\\n- A **unit fraction** has 1 on top -- like $\\\\tfrac{1}{4}$ -- a single equal part.\\n- When the numerator equals) Tj
T* ( the denominator, you have the **whole**: $\\\\tfrac{4}{4} = 1$.\\n- A bigger denominator means **more, smaller** slices: ) Tj
T* (eighths are smaller than quarters.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
