(              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Equivalent fractions** are fractions that name the **same amount**, like\\n\\n$$\\\\frac12 = ) Tj
T* (\\\\frac24 = \\\\frac36 = \\\\frac{4}{8}.$$\\n\\n**To build an equivalent fraction, multiply \(or divide\) the numerator and ) Tj
T* (denominator by the *same* number.** This works because you're really multiplying by 1 in disguise:\\n\\n$$\\\\frac12 \\\\times) Tj
T* ( \\\\frac22 = \\\\frac24, \\\\qquad \\\\frac12 \\\\times \\\\frac33 = \\\\frac36.$$\\n\\nMultiplying top and bottom by the same number ) Tj
T* (doesn't change the value -- only the *number of pieces* you cut it into.\\n\\n**Simplifying** \(or reducing\) runs this in ) Tj
T* (reverse: divide top and bottom by a common factor to reach **lowest terms** -- the simplest name, where the only common ) Tj
T* (factor left is 1.\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{6}{8} = \\\\frac{6 \\\\div 2}{8 \\\\div 2} = \\\\frac{3}{4}.$$\\n\\nTo simplify fastest, divide by ) Tj
T* (the **greatest common factor** of the two numbers. For $\\\\tfrac{6}{8}$ that's 2; for $\\\\tfrac{10}{15}$ it's 5, giving ) Tj
T* ($\\\\tfrac{2}{3}$. A fraction is in lowest terms when no number bigger than 1 divides both parts.") Tj
