T* (              "title": "Choosing the bigger share",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Two friends argue over who got more cake: one has $\\\\tfrac23$ of a small tart, the other ) Tj
T* ($\\\\tfrac34$ of an identical one. To settle it, you need to **compare** fractions. The trick depends on whether the ) Tj
T* (bottoms \(or tops\) match.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Same denominator?** Just compare the numerators -- more parts of the *same size* means ) Tj
T* (more.\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{3}{5} > \\\\frac{2}{5} \\\\quad \(\\\\text{3 fifths beat 2 fifths}\).$$\\n\\n**Same numerator?** The one with ) Tj
T* (the **smaller denominator** is larger, because the pieces are bigger.\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{1}{3} > \\\\frac{1}{4} \\\\quad \(\\\\text{a ) Tj
T* (third is a bigger slice than a quarter}\).$$\\n\\nThis surprises people: with the *same number* of pieces, **more pieces in) Tj
T* ( the whole means each is smaller**.\\n\\n**Neither matches?** Rewrite both with a **common denominator** \(a shared bottom ) Tj
T* (number\), then compare numerators. Compare $\\\\tfrac23$ and $\\\\tfrac34$ using denominator 12:\\n\\n$$\\\\frac23 = ) Tj
T* (\\\\frac{8}{12}, \\\\qquad \\\\frac34 = \\\\frac{9}{12} \\\\;\\\\Rightarrow\\\\; \\\\frac34 > \\\\frac23.$$\\n\\nA good common denominator ) Tj
T* (is any common multiple of the two bottoms \(the **least common multiple** is tidiest; multiplying the two denominators ) Tj
T* (always works too\). Once the bottoms match, the bigger top wins.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SIMULATION",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Try it: compare by eye",) Tj
