T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "At closing time the baker has $\\\\tfrac14$ of a pie on one plate and $\\\\tfrac24$ on another.) Tj
T* ( Boxed together, that's $\\\\tfrac34$ of a pie. But what if the slices are *different sizes* -- say $\\\\tfrac12$ and ) Tj
T* ($\\\\tfrac13$? Then we first have to make the pieces match.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Same denominator.** Add \(or subtract\) the **numerators** and keep the denominator -- the ) Tj
T* (slice size doesn't change, you just have more or fewer slices:\\n\\n$$\\\\frac14 + \\\\frac24 = \\\\frac{1+2}{4} = \\\\frac34, ) Tj
T* (\\\\qquad \\\\frac56 - \\\\frac16 = \\\\frac{4}{6} = \\\\frac23.$$\\n\\nAlways **simplify** the result if you can \($\\\\tfrac46 = ) Tj
T* (\\\\tfrac23$\).\\n\\n**Different denominators.** You can't add fourths to thirds any more than you can add apples to oranges ) Tj
T* (-- first rewrite both with a **common denominator**:\\n\\n$$\\\\frac12 + \\\\frac13: \\\\quad \\\\text{use 6} \\\\;\\\\Rightarrow\\\\; ) Tj
T* (\\\\frac{3}{6} + \\\\frac{2}{6} = \\\\frac{5}{6}.$$\\n\\nThe recipe:\\n\\n1. Find a common denominator \(a common multiple of the ) Tj
T* (bottoms\).\\n2. Rewrite each fraction with that denominator \(build equivalents\).\\n3. Add or subtract the numerators; keep ) Tj
T* (the denominator.\\n4. Simplify the answer.\\n\\nThe whole game is **making the slices the same size** before you combine ) Tj
T* (them.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SIMULATION",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Try it: build the sum",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "simId": "fraction-pie",) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Shade $\\\\tfrac14$, then $\\\\tfrac24$ on a pie cut into quarters to see $\\\\tfrac34$ appear. ) Tj
T* (Same-size slices simply add up.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
ET
