T* (              "title": "At the market stalls",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "The fruit seller stacks 6 apples next to 4 oranges. A juice stand mixes 3 cups of water ) Tj
T* (with 1 cup of concentrate. To describe these comparisons precisely, we use **ratios** -- the foundation of rates, ) Tj
T* (proportions, and percents, and one of the most useful ideas in everyday math.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A **ratio** compares two quantities. The ratio of 6 apples to 4 oranges can be written ) Tj
T* (three ways:\\n\\n$$6 : 4 \\\\qquad \\\\frac{6}{4} \\\\qquad \\\\text{\\"6 to 4\\".}$$\\n\\nLike fractions, ratios can be ) Tj
T* (**simplified** by dividing both parts by a common factor:\\n\\n$$6 : 4 = 3 : 2.$$\\n\\nTwo flavours of ratio:\\n\\n- ) Tj
T* (**Part-to-part** compares one group to another: apples to oranges, $6 : 4 = 3 : 2$.\\n- **Part-to-whole** compares one ) Tj
T* (group to the total: apples to all fruit, $6 : 10 = 3 : 5$ \(since $6 + 4 = 10$\).\\n\\nPart-to-whole ratios are just ) Tj
T* (fractions in disguise -- apples are $\\\\tfrac{6}{10} = \\\\tfrac35$ of the fruit.\\n\\nOrder matters: \\"apples to oranges\\" ) Tj
T* ($6:4$ is **not** the same as \\"oranges to apples\\" $4:6$. Always keep the quantities in the order named.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
