T* (              "kind": "DEEPER_DIVE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Deeper dive: ratios with more than two parts",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Ratios can compare **three or more** quantities at once. A fruit punch recipe might be $2 :) Tj
T* ( 3 : 5$ \(orange : pineapple : soda\). The parts still scale together: doubling gives $4 : 6 : 10$. And the **total ) Tj
T* (parts** \($2 + 3 + 5 = 10$\) let you turn any total amount into the right share -- for 20 cups of punch, each 'part' is 2 ) Tj
T* (cups, so you'd use 4, 6, and 10 cups. This 'parts' thinking is exactly how recipes, paint mixes, and concrete are scaled) Tj
T* ( in the real world.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SUMMARY",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Summary",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "takeaways": [) Tj
T* (                  "A ratio compares two quantities: $a:b$, $\\\\tfrac{a}{b}$, or 'a to b'.",) Tj
T* (                  "Simplify ratios by dividing both parts by a common factor.",) Tj
T* (                  "Part-to-part compares groups; part-to-whole compares to the total.",) Tj
T* (                  "Part-to-whole ratios are fractions.",) Tj
T* (                  "Order matters: $a:b \\\\ne b:a$.") Tj
T* (                ],) Tj
T* (                "formulas": [) Tj
