T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Scaling a recipe",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A recipe for 4 people needs 6 eggs. How many eggs for 6 people? Whenever two quantities ) Tj
T* (stay in the same ratio, you have a **proportion** -- and cross-multiplication finds any missing value. It's the engine ) Tj
T* (behind scaling recipes, reading maps, mixing chemicals, and converting currencies.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A **proportion** is a statement that **two ratios are equal**:\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{a}{b} = ) Tj
T* (\\\\frac{c}{d}.$$\\n\\nThe powerful tool for proportions is **cross-multiplication**: multiply each numerator by the other ) Tj
T* (denominator. If the ratios are equal, the cross-products are equal:\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{a}{b} = \\\\frac{c}{d} ) Tj
T* (\\\\;\\\\Longleftrightarrow\\\\; a \\\\times d = b \\\\times c.$$\\n\\nThis lets you **solve for an unknown**. To solve ) Tj
T* ($\\\\dfrac{x}{4} = \\\\dfrac{6}{8}$:\\n\\n$$8x = 4 \\\\times 6 = 24 \\\\;\\\\Rightarrow\\\\; x = 3.$$\\n\\nThe recipe for any proportion) Tj
T* ( problem:\\n\\n1. Write the two ratios, keeping units in the **same order** on top and bottom.\\n2. Cross-multiply.\\n3. ) Tj
T* (Solve the resulting simple equation.\\n\\nCross-multiplication is also the quickest **test** of whether two ratios are ) Tj
T* (equal: $\\\\tfrac23$ and $\\\\tfrac69$ give $2\\\\times9 = 18$ and $3\\\\times6 = 18$ -- equal, so they form a proportion.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
