(              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Percent** means **per hundred**, so $p\\\\% = \\\\dfrac{p}{100}$. To find **$p\\\\%$ of a ) Tj
T* (number $n$**, turn the percent into a decimal \(or fraction\) and **multiply**:\\n\\n$$p\\\\%\\\\ \\\\text{of}\\\\ n = ) Tj
T* (\\\\frac{p}{100} \\\\times n.$$\\n\\nFor example, $25\\\\%$ of $80$:\\n\\n$$\\\\frac{25}{100} \\\\times 80 = 0.25 \\\\times 80 = ) Tj
T* (20.$$\\n\\nHandy mental anchors:\\n\\n- **10%** -- just move the decimal one place: $10\\\\%$ of $50$ is $5$.\\n- **50%** -- ) Tj
T* (half: $50\\\\%$ of $90$ is $45$.\\n- **25%** -- a quarter: $25\\\\%$ of $80$ is $20$.\\n- **1%** -- move the decimal two ) Tj
T* (places: $1\\\\%$ of $300$ is $3$.\\n\\nYou can build other percents from these: $30\\\\%$ is three lots of $10\\\\%$; $15\\\\%$ is) Tj
T* ( $10\\\\% + 5\\\\%$ \(and $5\\\\%$ is half of $10\\\\%$\). This is how people compute tips in their heads.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SIMULATION",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Try it: see the percent",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "simId": "fraction-pie",) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Shade a fraction of the pie and read its percent. Seeing that $\\\\tfrac14$ of the whole is ) Tj
T* ($25\\\\%$ makes 'percent of a number' click -- a quarter of 80 is 20.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
