T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A **two-step equation** has the form $ax + b = c$. To solve, undo the operations in ) Tj
T* (**reverse order** of operations:\\n\\n1. **First undo addition/subtraction** \(the constant $b$\).\\n2. **Then undo ) Tj
T* (multiplication/division** \(the coefficient $a$\).\\n\\nFor $2m + 3 = 11$:\\n\\n$$2m + 3 - 3 = 11 - 3 \\\\;\\\\Rightarrow\\\\; 2m = ) Tj
T* (8 \\\\;\\\\Rightarrow\\\\; \\\\frac{2m}{2} = \\\\frac{8}{2} \\\\;\\\\Rightarrow\\\\; m = 4.$$\\n\\nWhy reverse order? When you *evaluate* ) Tj
T* ($2m + 3$ you multiply first, then add. To *undo*, you reverse the sequence: subtract first, then divide. Think of ) Tj
T* (unwrapping a gift -- last layer on goes first layer off.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
