T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Costing a building",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "An architect pricing a plot needs two numbers: the **perimeter** \(how much fencing or trim ) Tj
T* (to buy\) and the **area** \(how much floor or paint to cover\). They measure different things -- and confusing them is one ) Tj
T* (of the most common -- and expensive -- mistakes.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Perimeter** is the total distance around a shape -- add up all the side lengths. **Area**) Tj
T* ( is the amount of surface inside, measured in **square** units.\\n\\nThe essentials:\\n\\n- Rectangle: perimeter $P = 2\(l + ) Tj
T* (w\)$, area $A = l\\\\,w$.\\n- Square \(side $s$\): $P = 4s$, area $A = s^2$.\\n- Triangle \(base $b$, height $h$\): $A = ) Tj
T* (\\\\tfrac12 b h$.\\n- Circle \(radius $r$\): circumference $C = 2\\\\pi r$, area $A = \\\\pi r^2$.\\n\\nUnits matter: perimeter is ) Tj
T* (in length units \(m\), area in square units \(m^2\). Doubling the side of a square doubles its perimeter but **quadruples** ) Tj
T* (its area, because area depends on the side *squared*.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
