(              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "city",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "The Typical Value",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "When one number must summarize many, statistics offers three different 'centers' -- and they ) Tj
T* (don't always agree.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Reading the ticker",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A trader stares at a column of daily prices. What's the *typical* value? There isn't a ) Tj
T* (single answer -- there are three useful ones: the **mean**, the **median**, and the **mode**. Each tells a slightly ) Tj
T* (different story, and knowing which to trust is the heart of statistics.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Three **measures of center** summarize a data set:\\n\\n- **Mean** \(average\): add all values,) Tj
T* ( divide by how many. $\\\\bar x = \\\\dfrac{\\\\sum x}{n}$.\\n- **Median**: the middle value when the data is sorted \(the ) Tj
T* (average of the two middle values if $n$ is even\).\\n- **Mode**: the value that appears most often \(there may be none or ) Tj
T* (several\).\\n\\nFor $2, 3, 3, 6, 11$:\\n\\n- Mean $= \\\\dfrac{2+3+3+6+11}{5} = \\\\dfrac{25}{5} = 5$.\\n- Median $= 3$ \(the ) Tj
T* (middle of five sorted values\).\\n- Mode $= 3$ \(it appears twice\).\\n\\nThe **mean** is pulled by extreme values ) Tj
T* (\(**outliers**\); the **median** resists them. A single huge salary drags the mean up while the median barely moves -- ) Tj
T* (which is why incomes are usually reported as medians.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Mean",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Find the mean of $4, 8, 9, 3$.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Sum: $4+8+9+3 = 24$.",) Tj
T* (                      "Divide by 4.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Mean $= 6$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Median",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Find the median of $7, 2, 9, 4, 5$.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Sort: $2, 4, 5, 7, 9$.",) Tj
T* (                      "Middle of five is the 3rd.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "Median $= 5$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Outlier effect",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Why is median often preferred for incomes?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "A few huge incomes inflate the mean.",) Tj
T* (                      "The median ignores their size.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "The median resists outliers.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
T* (                ]) Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT_CHECK",) Tj
