T* (                "headline": "Beyond the Average",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "Two data sets can share a mean yet look completely different. Spread tells you how much the ) Tj
T* (values scatter.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Risk on the trading floor",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Two stocks both *average* a 5% return -- but one is steady while the other swings wildly. A) Tj
T* ( trader cares enormously about that difference: it's **risk**. Center alone can't capture it; you also need a measure of) Tj
T* ( **spread**.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "**Spread** measures how scattered the data is.\\n\\n- **Range** = maximum - minimum. Simple, ) Tj
T* (but only uses the two extremes.\\n- **Quartiles** split sorted data into four equal parts: $Q_1$ \(25%\), $Q_2$ \(the ) Tj
T* (median\), $Q_3$ \(75%\).\\n- **Interquartile range \(IQR\)** = $Q_3 - Q_1$ -- the spread of the middle half, which ignores ) Tj
T* (outliers.\\n\\nFor $3, 5, 7, 9, 11$: range $= 11 - 3 = 8$.\\n\\nA larger spread means the data is more variable -- less ) Tj
T* (predictable. Two sets with the same mean can have very different spreads, so a center and a spread together give a far ) Tj
T* (fuller picture than either alone.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
