stream
BT
/F1 7.2 Tf
8.6 TL
40 744.8 Td
(              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Machines on Gear Street",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Every machine in the district takes an input and produces an output: put in raw steel, get ) Tj
T* (out a bolt; put in $3$, get out $7$. A **function** is the mathematical version -- a rule that assigns to each input ) Tj
T* (**exactly one** output. That predictability is what makes functions the language of science and engineering.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A **function** assigns to every input exactly **one** output. We write\\n\\n$$f\(x\) = 2x + ) Tj
T* (1,$$\\n\\nread '$f$ of $x$ equals $2x+1$'. Here $x$ is the **input**; $f\(x\)$ is the **output**.\\n\\n- To **evaluate**, ) Tj
T* (substitute: $f\(3\) = 2\(3\) + 1 = 7$.\\n- The **domain** is the set of allowed inputs; the **range** is the set of outputs ) Tj
T* (produced.\\n- The defining rule: **one input -> one output**. A relation that sends one input to two different outputs is) Tj
T* ( *not* a function.\\n\\n**Vertical line test:** on a graph, if any vertical line crosses the curve more than once, it ) Tj
T* (fails -- that input would have two outputs, so it isn't a function.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Evaluate",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "For $f\(x\) = 2x + 1$, find $f\(3\)$.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Substitute $x = 3$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$2\(3\) + 1 = 7$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$f\(3\) = 7$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Evaluate at a negative",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "For $f\(x\) = x^2 - 1$, find $f\(-2\)$.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$\(-2\)^2 - 1$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$4 - 1 = 3$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$f\(-2\) = 3$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Function or not?",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Does the rule 'output any number whose square is the input' define a function?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Input 9 could give 3 or -3.",) Tj
T* (                      "One input, two outputs.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "No -- it is not a function.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
T* (                ]) Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT_CHECK",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Quick check",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "One input, exactly one output.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "PRACTICE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Practice problems",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Substitute carefully; watch signs.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "DEEPER_DIVE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Deeper dive: composing functions",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Functions can be chained: the output of one becomes the input of the next. If $f\(x\) = 2x$ ) Tj
T* (and $g\(x\) = x + 1$, then $f\(g\(x\)\) = f\(x+1\) = 2\(x+1\) = 2x + 2$. This **composition**, written $\(f \\\\circ g\)\(x\)$, is how ) Tj
T* (complex processes are built from simple steps -- and reversing a function gives its **inverse**, the idea behind ) Tj
T* (logarithms and square roots.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SUMMARY",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Summary",) Tj
ET
endstream
