(              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Why degrees aren't enough",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Right-triangle trig stops at $90^\\\\circ$ -- but wheels, waves, and orbits turn far past ) Tj
T* (that. The **unit circle** extends sine and cosine to *any* angle, and **radians** give angles a natural measure tied ) Tj
T* (directly to arc length, the unit calculus and physics demand.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Place a circle of radius $1$ at the origin. For an angle $\\\\theta$ measured from the ) Tj
T* (positive $x$-axis, the point on the circle is\\n\\n$$\(\\\\cos\\\\theta, \\\\sin\\\\theta\).$$\\n\\nSo **cosine is the $x$-coordinate ) Tj
T* (and sine is the $y$-coordinate** -- definitions that work for *any* angle, including those past $90^\\\\circ$ and negative) Tj
T* ( ones.\\n\\n**Radians** measure an angle by the **arc length** it subtends on the unit circle. A full circle is $2\\\\pi$ ) Tj
T* (radians $= 360^\\\\circ$, so:\\n\\n$$180^\\\\circ = \\\\pi \\\\text{ rad}, \\\\qquad 90^\\\\circ = \\\\tfrac{\\\\pi}{2}, \\\\qquad 1\\\\text{ ) Tj
T* (rad} \\\\approx 57.3^\\\\circ.$$\\n\\nConvert with $\\\\text{rad} = \\\\text{deg} \\\\times \\\\dfrac{\\\\pi}{180}$. Key values: $\\\\cos ) Tj
T* (0 = 1$, $\\\\sin 0 = 0$, $\\\\sin\\\\tfrac{\\\\pi}{2} = 1$, $\\\\cos\\\\pi = -1$.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Degrees to radians",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Convert $90^\\\\circ$ to radians.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$\\\\times \\\\pi/180$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$90\\\\pi/180 = \\\\pi/2$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$\\\\tfrac{\\\\pi}{2}$ rad.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "A coordinate",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "What point on the unit circle is at $\\\\theta = 0$?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "$\(\\\\cos 0, \\\\sin 0\)$.",) Tj
T* (                      "$\(1, 0\)$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$\(1, 0\)$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Past 90 deg",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "What is the sign of $\\\\sin\\\\theta$ for $\\\\theta = 200^\\\\circ$?",) Tj
