T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "PRACTICE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Practice problems",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Convert angles and read unit-circle coordinates.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "DEEPER_DIVE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Deeper dive: why radians make calculus clean",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Radians aren't just convenient -- they're *necessary* for calculus. Only in radians is ) Tj
T* ($\\\\lim_{x \\\\to 0} \\\\dfrac{\\\\sin x}{x} = 1$, which makes the derivative of $\\\\sin x$ exactly $\\\\cos x$. In degrees that ) Tj
T* (derivative picks up an ugly factor of $\\\\pi/180$. Because radians tie angle directly to arc length, every rotational ) Tj
T* (formula in physics -- angular velocity, torque, wave phase -- is written in radians.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
