T* (          "slug": "exponential-growth-and-decay",) Tj
T* (          "title": "Exponential Growth & Decay",) Tj
T* (          "tagline": "When the rate depends on the amount",) Tj
T* (          "estMinutes": 15,) Tj
T* (          "xpReward": 160,) Tj
T* (          "difficulty": 4,) Tj
T* (          "sections": [) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "HERO",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "scene": "city",) Tj
T* (                "headline": "Doubling and Halving",) Tj
T* (                "sub": "Multiply by the same factor again and again, and quantities explode -- or vanish -- ) Tj
T* (astonishingly fast.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "From rumors to radioactivity",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A rumor that doubles its reach each hour, a savings account compounding interest, a ) Tj
T* (radioactive sample halving every few years -- all follow the same law. **Exponential** change multiplies by a constant ) Tj
T* (factor each step, in contrast to **linear** change, which adds a constant. The difference becomes staggering quickly.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "An **exponential function** has the variable in the **exponent**:\\n\\n$$f\(x\) = ) Tj
T* (a\\\\,b^{x},$$\\n\\nwhere $a$ is the starting value and $b$ is the **growth factor**.\\n\\n- If $b > 1$, it's **growth** \(e.g.) Tj
T* ( $b = 2$ doubles each step\).\\n- If $0 < b < 1$, it's **decay** \(e.g. $b = \\\\tfrac12$ halves each step\).\\n\\nKey contrasts) Tj
T* ( with linear functions:\\n\\n- Linear *adds* a fixed amount; exponential *multiplies* by a fixed factor.\\n- Exponential ) Tj
T* (growth has a constant **doubling time**; decay has a constant **half-life**.\\n- The graph of $b^x$ is always positive, ) Tj
T* (rising steeply \(growth\) or falling toward zero \(decay\) but never reaching it.\\n\\nThe special base $e \\\\approx 2.718$ ) Tj
T* (gives the smoothest, 'natural' exponential $e^x$, central to all of calculus and continuous growth.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
