T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A **logarithm** is the inverse of an exponential. By definition,\\n\\n$$\\\\log_b y = x \\\\iff ) Tj
T* (b^{x} = y.$$\\n\\nIn words: $\\\\log_b y$ is the power you raise $b$ to in order to get $y$. For example $\\\\log_2 8 = 3$ ) Tj
T* (because $2^3 = 8$.\\n\\nCommon bases: $\\\\log_{10}$ \('log', used for pH and decibels\) and $\\\\log_e = \\\\ln$ \(the 'natural ) Tj
T* (log'\).\\n\\nThe **laws of logarithms** turn multiplication into addition:\\n\\n$$\\\\log\(xy\) = \\\\log x + \\\\log y, \\\\quad ) Tj
T* (\\\\log\\\\!\\\\frac{x}{y} = \\\\log x - \\\\log y, \\\\quad \\\\log\(x^n\) = n\\\\log x.$$\\n\\nThese laws are why logarithms historically ) Tj
T* (powered slide rules and hand computation, and why they appear whenever we solve for a variable stuck in an exponent.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
