(                "markdown": "The **limit** of $f\(x\)$ as $x$ approaches $a$ is the value $f\(x\)$ gets arbitrarily close to) Tj
T* ( as $x$ gets close to $a$ -- written\\n\\n$$\\\\lim_{x \\\\to a} f\(x\) = L.$$\\n\\nCrucially, the limit is about the ) Tj
T* (**approach**, not the value *at* $a$ -- the function need not even be defined there.\\n\\n- For a 'nice' \(continuous\) ) Tj
T* (function, just substitute: $\\\\lim_{x\\\\to 2}\(x^2\) = 4$.\\n- The famous case is $f\(x\) = \\\\dfrac{x^2 - 1}{x - 1}$. At $x = ) Tj
T* (1$ it's $\\\\tfrac00$ -- undefined. But for every other $x$ it simplifies to $x + 1$, so as $x \\\\to 1$ the function ) Tj
T* (approaches $2$. The limit is $2$ even though $f\(1\)$ doesn't exist.\\n\\nA limit exists only if the approach from the ) Tj
T* (**left** and from the **right** agree.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Worked examples",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "examples": [) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Substitute",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Find $\\\\lim_{x\\\\to 3}\(2x + 1\)$.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Continuous -- substitute.",) Tj
T* (                      "$2\(3\) + 1 = 7$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$7$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "Indeterminate form",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Find $\\\\lim_{x\\\\to 1}\\\\dfrac{x^2 - 1}{x - 1}$.",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Factor: $\\\\dfrac{\(x-1\)\(x+1\)}{x-1}$.",) Tj
T* (                      "Cancel: $x + 1$.",) Tj
T* (                      "As $x\\\\to1$: $2$.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$2$.") Tj
T* (                  },) Tj
T* (                  {) Tj
T* (                    "title": "One-sided check",) Tj
T* (                    "problem": "Why might a limit fail to exist?",) Tj
T* (                    "steps": [) Tj
T* (                      "Left and right approaches differ.",) Tj
T* (                      "Then there's no single value.") Tj
T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "The two sides disagree.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
T* (                ]) Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT_CHECK",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Quick check",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "A limit is what the function approaches, not its value at the point.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "PRACTICE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Practice problems",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Substitute when continuous; factor to resolve 0/0.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "DEEPER_DIVE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Deeper dive: limits build the derivative",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "The slope of a curve at a single point is a $\\\\tfrac00$ puzzle -- you'd need two points to ) Tj
T* (find a slope, but you only have one. Limits resolve it: take the slope between $x$ and a nearby $x + h$, then let $h ) Tj
T* (\\\\to 0$. That limit, $\\\\displaystyle\\\\lim_{h\\\\to 0}\\\\dfrac{f\(x+h\)-f\(x\)}{h}$, is the **derivative** -- the exact ) Tj
T* (instantaneous rate of change. Every idea in differential calculus rests on the limit you've just met.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "SUMMARY",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Summary",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "takeaways": [) Tj
T* (                  "A limit is the value $f\(x\)$ approaches as $x \\\\to a$.",) Tj
T* (                  "It concerns the approach, not the value at $a$.",) Tj
