T* (                    ],) Tj
T* (                    "answer": "$9$.") Tj
T* (                  }) Tj
T* (                ]) Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT_CHECK",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Quick check",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Integration adds one to the power and divides.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "PRACTICE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Practice problems",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "intro": "Find antiderivatives; evaluate definite integrals as $F\(b\)-F\(a\)$.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "DEEPER_DIVE",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Deeper dive: why area and antiderivatives are the same",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Let $A\(x\)$ be the area under $f$ from a fixed start up to $x$. Nudge $x$ by a tiny $h$: the) Tj
T* ( extra area is a sliver of width $h$ and height about $f\(x\)$, so $A\(x+h\) - A\(x\) \\\\approx f\(x\)\\\\,h$. Divide by $h$ and ) Tj
T* (let $h\\\\to0$: $A'\(x\) = f\(x\)$. The area function *is* an antiderivative -- that is the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, ) Tj
ET
endstream
