T* (              "title": "Decay, interest, and epidemics",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Radioactive decay, continuously compounded interest, the early spread of a disease -- all ) Tj
T* (obey the same DE, $\\\\dfrac{dy}{dt} = ky$. Its solution is the single most important function in applied mathematics: the) Tj
T* ( exponential.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "The DE $\\\\dfrac{dy}{dt} = k\\\\,y$ -- rate proportional to amount -- has the general ) Tj
T* (solution\\n\\n$$y\(t\) = y_0\\\\,e^{kt},$$\\n\\nwhere $y_0 = y\(0\)$ is the initial value.\\n\\n- If $k > 0$: **exponential growth**) Tj
T* ( \(population, interest\).\\n- If $k < 0$: **exponential decay** \(radioactivity, cooling\).\\n\\nWhy $e$? Because ) Tj
T* ($\\\\dfrac{d}{dt}e^{kt} = k\\\\,e^{kt}$ -- the exponential is the unique function \(up to scale\) whose derivative is ) Tj
T* (proportional to itself, exactly what the DE demands.\\n\\nThe **half-life** \(decay\) or **doubling time** \(growth\) is ) Tj
T* (constant and depends only on $|k|$: doubling time $= \\\\dfrac{\\\\ln 2}{k}$. This is why carbon dating works -- decay is ) Tj
T* (perfectly regular.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
