T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONTEXT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "Making calculus rigorous",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "Calculus works, but *why*? Real analysis rebuilds it on a precise foundation, starting with) Tj
T* ( **sequences** and what it means for them to **converge**. The payoff is certainty: theorems that hold without ) Tj
T* (exception, proved from definitions rather than pictures.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "CONCEPT",) Tj
T* (              "title": "The big idea",) Tj
T* (              "content": {) Tj
T* (                "markdown": "A **sequence** is an ordered, infinite list $a_1, a_2, a_3, \\\\dots$. It **converges** to a ) Tj
T* (limit $L$ if its terms get and stay arbitrarily close to $L$.\\n\\nThe rigorous \($\\\\varepsilon$-$N$\) definition:\\n\\n> $a_n) Tj
T* ( \\\\to L$ means: for every $\\\\varepsilon > 0$ there is an $N$ such that $|a_n - L| < \\\\varepsilon$ for all $n > N$.\\n\\nIn) Tj
T* ( words: name any tolerance $\\\\varepsilon$, however tiny, and eventually every term lands within $\\\\varepsilon$ of ) Tj
T* ($L$.\\n\\nExamples:\\n\\n- $a_n = \\\\dfrac{1}{n} \\\\to 0$.\\n- $a_n = \\\\dfrac{n+1}{n} = 1 + \\\\dfrac1n \\\\to 1$.\\n- $a_n = ) Tj
T* (\(-1\)^n$ **diverges** -- it bounces between $-1$ and $1$, never settling.\\n\\nA sequence that doesn't converge ) Tj
T* (**diverges**. Convergence is the bedrock idea on which limits, continuity, derivatives, and integrals are all rigorously) Tj
T* ( built.") Tj
T* (              }) Tj
T* (            },) Tj
T* (            {) Tj
T* (              "kind": "WORKED_EXAMPLES",) Tj
